<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian City of Agra Greets Clinton With Tight  Security, Protests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Reports reaching here said the entire city resembled a military
garrison with armed para-military personnel guarding every nook
and corner to prevent any untoward incident during Clinton's visit.
</P>
<P>
The Press Trust of India (PTI) reported from the scene that
only a few reporters were allowed to cover his visit to Taj Mahal,
one of the seven wonders of the world, leading to heated arguments
between journalists and officials.
</P>
<P>
The media personnel, most of whom were from New Delhi to cover
the event, were thoroughly frisked by U.S. security officials, PTI
said.
</P>
<P>
The tight security measures were taken following a bomb blast
on March 18 in a bus near city, in which a woman was killed and 16
others were injured.
</P>
<P>
The security was accompanied by noisy demonstrations by left
party activists who took on a march to Taj Mahal waving black
flags, holding placards and shouting anti-Clinton and anti-U.S.
slogans, PTI said, adding some of them were detained by the police.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the agency said, people in the city, known
for their hospitality, remained by and large cool to Clinton's
visit, a sharp contrast to their past enthusiastic response to
other world leaders including former Chinese Premier Zhou En Lai
and former Soviet leader Nikita Khruschev.
</P>
<P>
PTI quoted a old citizen in Agra as saying that when Zhou En
Lai came for a visit in 1955, people and school children
spontaneously lined up all along the entire route to the Taj to
give him a warm welcome. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
