<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Protests to Ukraine for Shooting at Turkish Fishing Boats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Foreign Ministry Thursday
summoned Ukrainian Ambassador to Ankara Oleksandr Motsyk to protest
against Ukrainian coast guards who killed two fishermen when
opening fire on Turkish fishing boats in the Black Sea.
</P>
<P>
The Ukrainian coast guards on Wednesday shot at five Turkish
boats which they claimed were fishing in Ukrainian territorial
waters without getting permission, killing two fishermen and
sinking two boats.
</P>
<P>
Turkey asked Ukraine to take necessary measures to prevent re-
occurrence of similar incidents and guarantee compensation, the
Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The fishermen's association of Turkey harshly reacted to the
incident. Staging a press conference, Ismet Yalcin, chairman of
Istanbul Fish Producers Association, said that when the Ukrainian
Coast Guard boats opened fire, the five Turkish fishing boats were
sailing nearly 110 miles south of Ukrainian shores.
</P>
<P>
"Whatever the reason was, murder of a Turkish fisherman and fire
opened by coast guard boats can't suit principles of maritime,
modernity, and humanity. We condemn this attack," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Zafer Murat Cetintas, advisor of the Association, accused
Ukraine of continuously polluting the Marmara Sea and the Black Sea
with its oil tankers and heavy metals.
</P>
<P>
He said that he couldn't understand the reason for Ukraine's
opening fire on fishing boats in a peaceful atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
Recently, Ukrainian Foreign Minister Boris Tarasyuk paid his
first official visit to Turkey to expand bilateral trade and
economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Turco-Ukraine relations recorded rapid progress after the former
republic of Soviet Union won independence in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Also, Ukraine is one of the countries that support Turkey's
initiative for the establishment of the Black Sea economic
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Ahmet Menekse, chairman of the Marmara Fishermen's Cooperatives,
said that fire can't be opened on a ship in accordance with
international laws.
</P>
<P>
Recalling that he encountered a similar attack on March 13, 1991
in international waters, Sariyer Fishermen's Cooperative Chairman
Mehmet Sahin said their boat was riddled after the attack.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the maximum speed of the fishing boats can be 12
miles per hour, Sahin said the Ukrainian coast guard boats can
catch fishing boats without opening fire. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
