<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia's TB Cases on Increase: Health Ministry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, March 23 (Xinhua) -- The Ethiopian Health Ministry
said Thursday that the number of people who are suffering from
tuberculosis (TB) is on the increase despite of national efforts
to curb the killer disease.
</P>
<P>
Although Ethiopia has implemented Direct Observation Treatments
(Dots) strategy recommended by the World Health Organization,
only 65 percent of the patients get cured, the ministry said in a
statement issued on the eve of the World TB Day to be observed on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
TB has seriously affected citizens in the age group of 14-45
who could be instrumental in the nation building process, the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that there were 250,000 TB patients in Ethiopia
by mid- 1999. Ethiopia launched Dots strategy in 1992 in a bid to
reduce TB cases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
