<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arabs Stress Support for Unity of Syrian, Lebanese Tracks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Arab League Secretary General Esmat
Abdel-Meguid reiterated on Thursday the Arab support for and
adherence to the integrity of the Syrian and Lebanese tracks in
peace talks with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after meeting with a visiting Hungarian
parliamentary delegation, Abdel-Meguid rejected Israel's attempts
to sap the organic unity of Syria and Lebanon, saying that such
attempts were doomed to failure.
</P>
<P>
Syria, which stations more than 30,000 troops in Lebanon as
peacekeepers, has decisive influence on Beirut. The two countries
agree not to separate their peace negotiations with Israel for the
return of occupied territories. But Israel has been striving to
drive a wedge between the northern neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid voiced hope that the Geneva summit between Syrian
President Hafez al-Assad and United States President Bill Clinton
on Sunday would lead to progress on the Syrian and Lebanese tracks.
</P>
<P>
He urged the U.S. to press Israel into taking tangible steps to
withdraw to the June 4, 1967 borders. He underlined the support of
the Arab countries for the just Syrian and Lebanese demand for
Israeli pullback from the Golan Heights and southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel occupied Syria's Golan in the 1967 Mideast War and set up
a so-called security zone in southern Lebanon in 1985.
</P>
<P>
The Hungarian parliamentary delegation is due to leave here on
Saturday for Israel and the Palestinian self-rule areas in a
regional tour. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000323.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Texas Lawmakers Express Solidarity With Palestinians on Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Showing support to the Middle East
peace process, 13 U.S. parliamentarians expressed on Thursday
solidarity with the Palestinian people on their rights to
Jerusalem, the Palestinian News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Texas lawmakers expressed the attitude after a meeting with
three members of the Palestinian Legislative Council (PLC) in the
West Bank town of Ramallah.
</P>
<P>
The two sides reviewed the political situation and the status of
Jerusalem. The Palestinian legislators briefed their guests on
the "Israeli occupational measures" in the Holy City and stressed
the Arab nature of it as capital of a future Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed that the Palestinian existance in the Holy
City was "original and deeply-rooted in the history" while the
Israeli existance in it has "an occupational and transient nature."
</P>
<P>
It is impossible to establish peace without the return of the
Holy City to full Palestinian sovereignty, the two sided said.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side urged the U.S. parliamentarians to adopt a
more decisive stance towards Israel based on relevant resolutions
of the United Nations Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Israel seized the Arab East Jerusalem from Jordan in the 1967
Middle East war. It declares that Jerusalem is the "indivisible and
eternal" capital of Israel while the Palestinians insists that East
Jerusalem would be the capital of their future independent state.
</P>
<P>
The status of Jerusalem is among the toughest issues to be
discussed in the final-status talks between the two sides, which
are expected to conclude in September.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Congress adopted a few years ago a resolution
recognizing Israel's sovereignty over Jerusalem and urging the
government to move the U.S. embassy from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem.
However, U.S. President Bill Clinton postponed the implementation
of the decision. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000323.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab League Urges Israel to Work for Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Arab League Secretary General Esmat
Abdel-Meguid on Thursday called on Israel to work for the
realization of peace with Arab neighbors in a bid to ensure the
security it seeks.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after meeting with Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat, Abdel-Meguid said that Israel's security could not
be achieved by force, threats to scorch Lebanon, evasion from its
commitments or by devising crisis.
</P>
<P>
The security could only be brought about by a clear and honest
commitment to the peace march based on the land-for-peace principle
and the implementation of the United Nations Security Council
resolutions 242, 388 and 425, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
These resolutions call for Israeli withdrawal from Syria's Golan
Heights to the June 4, 1967 borders, immediate and unconditional
pullback from south Lebanon and the Western Bekaa and establishment
of an independent Palestinian state with Jerusalem as its capital,
he added.
</P>
<P>
Israel occupied the Golan Heights in the 1967 Mideast War and
set up a so-called security zone in south Lebanon in 1985 allegely
to protect its northern areas from attack by Lebanese Muslim
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
The chief of the pan-Arab forum strongly condemned Israel's
repeated aggressive operations on Lebanon, stressing the need to
put an end to such acts. The league is holding contacts with
influential powers in the region to press Israel into halting its
aggressive offensives, Abdel-Meguid said.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid said that he discussed with Arafat the latest
developments of the Arab-Israeli peace process, especially on the
Palestinian track.
</P>
<P>
Contacts will be maintained between the league and the
Palestinian National Authority in the coming phase to follow up the
efforts exerted to push forward the peace talks, he added.
</P>
<P>
He expressed cautious optimism for achieving a progress in the
peace march on the Syrian, Palestinian and Lebanese tracks.
</P>
<P>
Arafat left here earlier in the day after a two-day visit to
Egypt. He frequently visits Egypt to discuss with President Hosni
Mubarak the peace talks with Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
