<DOCNO> XIE20000323.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FAO Stresses Food Security and Sustainable Development for Developing Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Director-General of the U.N. Food
and Agriculture Organization (FAO) on Thursday urged developing
countries to pay more attention to food security and achieve
sustainable agricultural development.
</P>
<P>
Jacques Diouf, the FAO chief, made the remarks at the 25th FAO
Regional Conference for the Near East, which is being held in
Beirut on March 20-24 and is attended by 29 countries.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the world cereal production in 1999 dropped
1 percent from 1998 to reach 1,872 million tons, which, for the
first time in four years, made cereal consumption exceed
production.
</P>
<P>
Diouf said that at the end of 1999, 52 million people in 35
countries were faced with food emergencies resulting from natural
or human disasters.
</P>
<P>
Under such circumstances, he added, the role of FAO, which aims
to alleviate malnutrition and hunger, and serves as a coordinating
agency for development programs in the whole range of food,
agriculture, forestry and fisheries, is more important than ever.
</P>
<P>
Referring to other "crises" facing world food industry, such as
mad cow disease and the presence of dioxin and listeria in the food
chain, Diouf said such "crisis" which occurred in developed
countries have created concern in developing countries which do not
have sufficient capacity of analysis.
</P>
<P>
The organization must respond to these challenges and its
concerned bodies are working to draft codes of conduct and
determine international standards for food security, he added.
</P>
<P>
As for agricultural development, the leader of the world's
biggest agricultural agency reiterated that developing countries
must improve the basis of sustainable development, especially water
policy.
</P>
<P>
The FAO, founded in 1945 and having 179 member countries and one
member organization, is the largest specialized agency in the
United Nations system and the leading agency for agriculture,
forestry, fisheries, and rural development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
