<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia, U.S. to Strengthen Cooperation in United Nations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Russia and the United
States both said here Thursday that they agree to strengthen their
cooperation in the United Nations in order to make the world body
"more efficient and more responsive to the challenges of the new
millennium."
</P>
<P>
The agreement was jointly announced by Sergey Lavrov, Russian
permanent representative to the United Nations, and Richard
Holbrooke, U.S. permanent representative to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
"The Russian Federation and the United States agree to
intensify Russian-American cooperation in the United Nations in
order to promote broad agreement on practical ways and means to
support the reform process with the aim of making the United
Nations more efficient and more responsive to the challenges of
the new millennium," a brief joint statement, read by Lavrov to
the press here, said.
</P>
<P>
"The Russian Federation and the United States share an
obligation to encourage the United Nations to the greatest
possible effectiveness and efficiency, especially in maintaining
and enhancing international peace and security in accordance with
the U.N. Charter," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"Our ministers asked their ambassadors in New York and their
respective ministries to work together with others towards this
end," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
Russia and the United States are two of the five permanent
members with veto power on the 15-nation U.N. Security Council,
which, under the U.N. Charter, has the primary responsibility for
the maintenance of peace and security in the world.
</P>
<P>
The joint statement came after the meeting in Lisbon early in
March between U.S. State of Secretary Madeleine Albright and
Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov.
</P>
<P>
The joint statement was also released just before the Fifth
Committee of the General Assembly, which is in charge of
administrative and budgetary affairs, will begin discussion of the
U.N. reform issues, including finance and membership dues,
Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
Both the ambassadors stopped short of giving detailed
explanation of the joint statement, saying that they will work
with other countries, including the other permanent members of
Security Council, on relevant issues.
</P>
<P>
"We're also going to work closely together with the other
members, P-5 (five permanent members of the Council) and other
countries," Holbrooke said. "What we are trying to do here is to
stimulate a much more intensive effort towards reform and with the
original founding member states take a leading role."
</P>
<P>
"I can't give you specifics now because we're still working
them out," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Lavrov said that the joint statement is "a general
statement of policy, and the details would be worked out not only
between our two countries, but with the participation of P-5, as
Ambassador Holbrooke said, and other members of the United Nations.
"
</P>
<P>
"As far as the budgetary reform is concerned, Russia is
prepared to negotiate resolution which will be a consensus
resolution," Lavrov said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
