<HEADLINE> Greek Stocks Continue Downward Course </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ATHENS, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Equity prices in Greece Thursday
continued its downward course with the general index on the Athens
Stock Exchange (ASE) ending at 4,650.77 points, down 1.53 percent.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE/ASE 20 index dropped 1.10 percent to 2,620.09 points
while the FTSE/ASE 40 index ended 3.22 percent lower at 686.60
points.
</P>
<P>
Turnover was 142 billion drachmas (about 412 million U.S.
dollars), its lowest levels since the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
Decliners led advancers by 300 to 34 with another 17 issues
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The construction and investment sectors led the declining
stock market, lowering 4.26 percent and 2.71 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis
Thursday said in Lisbon, Portugal, that the Athens bourse was
already in contact with other European stock exchanges, and it was
following the road of integration, which is expected to be
completed in 2001 with the single stock market having three pylons,
London, Frankfurt and Paris.
</P>
<P>
A pan-European stock market will offer Greek investors an
expanded investment product range, while Greek businesses could be
listed in this market and raise capital in other European
countries, according to Greek Economy and Finance Minister Yiannos
Papantoniou. 
</P>
</TEXT>
