<HEADLINE> Ruling PASOK Maintains Small Lead in Voter Preference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ATHENS, March 23 (Xinhua) -- With the April 9 national
elections drawing near, Greece's ruling Panhellenic Socialist
Movement (PASOK) has so far continued to maintain a marginal lead
over the country's main opposition New Democracy (ND), according
to the results of two opinion polls released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In the opinion poll, PASKO held a small 0.4 percentage point
lead over the ND, with the ruling party leading with 35.1 percent
followed closely by the ND with 34.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the MRB poll, which was conducted on March 7-17 on a sample
of 2,000 people, PASOK led with 34.5 percent over the ND with 34.2
percent.
</P>
<P>
Incumbent Premier Costas Simitis retained a comfortable
precedence over ND leader Costas Karamanlis.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the two polls showed that more than 50 percent of
the respondents believed that PASOK would win the coming
parliamentary elections, the 10th since the restoration of
democracy in Greece in 1974.
</P>
<P>
On March 14, Greek President Costis Stephanopoulos dissolved
the parliament, signaling the official start of the country's
election campaign, which is taking place mainly between the two
largest political parties in Greece.
</P>
<P>
The last parliamentary elections in Greece were held in
September 1996, with the ruling PASOK being re-elected by
obtaining 41.49 percent of the votes and getting 162 seats in the
300-member parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
