<HEADLINE> France Regrets Increasing Violation of Truce in D.R.Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 23 (Xinhua) -- France expressed strong regret
Thursday over what it called the increasing acts of violation of
the truce in the Democratic Republic of Congo (D.R.Congo) by both
sides of the war.
</P>
<P>
Rwandan troops and Congolese rebels took last week from
government forces the city of Idumbe in Kasai province, 750
kilometers east of Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government forces are making offensives in the
northwestern front in Equateur province and in the southern
province of Katanga against the rebels.
</P>
<P>
"France is worried by the general reinforcement of the military
forces of the conflicting parties which seems to be a prelude to a
revival of fightings. It is also concerned about the declarations
of some rebel leaders that the truce is no longer in force," said
French Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Anne Gazeau-Secret.
</P>
<P>
France also expressed concern about the difficulties being met
by the U.N. personnel who are in the D.R.Congo on a peace mission.
</P>
<P>
"France appeals to all the parties of the conflict to meet
their commitment and especially to respect the truce, without
which the deployment of the U.N. peacekeeping force, the MONUC,
cannot take place," said the spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
She also appeals to all Congolese parties to engage in national
dialogue as is called for by the Lusaka agreement, and to
cooperate with the mediator appointed by the Organization of
African Unity (OAU), former Botswana President Quett Masire.
</P>
<P>
The D.R.Congo government and its ally countries signed with
Rwanda and Uganda, two countries which back the Congolese rebels,
a truce agreement last July in Lusaka, but the agreement has been
incessantly violated by both sides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
