<HEADLINE> Austrian Minister Criticizes EU Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LISBON, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Austrian Finance Minister Heinz
Grasser, who is a member of the far-right Freedom Party, Thursday
accused the European Union of creating a situation of
discrimination between "good and bad" Europeans.
</P>
<P>
The finance minister, who is attending the two-day European
Union summit in Lisbon, said that Austrian students were paying
the price for the political sanctions by Austria's EU partners.
</P>
<P>
He said that Austrian students could no longer visit France and
that in his opinion the EU had opened "a breach" in the
fundamental treaty of the 15-nation bloc by not consulting the
Austrian government on the measures introduced.
</P>
<P>
He was talking about the bilateral political sanctions agreed
upon by the 14 EU member states to isolate Austria that swore in a
coalition government with Joerg Haider's ultra-right Freedom Party.
</P>
<P>
The minister hoped that the Lisbon summit would mark the
beginning of a process to normalize bilateral relations between
his country and the other EU member states, especially France and
Belgium that have been publicly cold-shouldering Austrian
government officials since early February.
</P>
<P>
When asked about the possibility of the Freedom Party changing
its political make-up, a pre-condition set by Portuguese Prime
Minister Antonio Guterres for the 14 EU member states to lift the
sanctions, the Austrian finance minister said that his party had
already given a "clear signal" on this matter.
</P>
<P>
He hinted at the facts that Haider has resigned from the
presidency of the Freedom Party and the Freedom Party has
expressed by signing the coalition government preamble its faith
in the democratic values and respect for human rights as required
by the Amsterdam Treaty of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
When asked to comment on the shift from the traditional "family
photo" of EU leaders to a group photo with EU leaders and the
visiting Mexican president, Grasser said that it was diplomatic
language.
</P>
<P>
The traditional EU "family photo" at the summit was substituted
by a group photo after French President Jacques Chirac and Belgian
Prime Minister Guy Verhofstadt threatened to stay away from the
family photo opportunity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
