<HEADLINE> France Opposes Gas, Transport Liberalization: Source </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LISBON, March 23 (Xinhua) -- France, one of the two economic
growth engines of the European Union, was opposed to the
liberalization of gas and transport markets that may hinder the
adoption of a final conclusion of the Lisbon EU summit.
</P>
<P>
The Portuguese news service Lusa quoted a French source as
saying that the insistence of some EU member states on opening the
French market was excessive.
</P>
<P>
"The French side does not hold this view," said the source who
was afraid that the competitiveness of the market would otherwise
have negative effects on the social dimension.
</P>
<P>
The exploitation of the complete potential of a European area
without frontiers through the total liberalization of the energy,
transport and financial service sectors is considered to be one of
the keys to success of the economic reform being discussed by the
heads of state and government from the 15 EU member states.
</P>
<P>
The plan to further exploit the potential of the EU internal
market is popular with the national governments of Britain, Spain
and Portugal but was opposed to by France, where the state is ever
present in strategic domains of the economy or where public and
social service priorities are high.
</P>
<P>
The EU leaders, prime ministers, foreign ministers and finance
ministers plus the French and Finnish presidents are trying to
look for solutions that allow the 15-nation bloc to imitate the
United States in the fight against unemployment and in the
qualification of work force for the knowledge-based economy.
</P>
<P>
They are discussing the draft proposal worked out by Portugal,
that is holding the six-month rotating presidency of the European
Union, in order to outline a strategy that is expected to help
reverse the lag of Europe as against the United States in the
information society and in the IT industry that generate jobs as
well as wealth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
