<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Botswana is investigating an
Irish- born citizen alleged to have provided supplies to the
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) in
violation of the UN sanctions, Botswanan Foreign Minister Mompati
Merafhe said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Dennis Coghlan was named by British Foreign Affairs Minister of
State for Africa Peter Hain in February as an alleged buster
against the UN's arms, fuel, travel and diamond trade embargo on
UNITA.
</P>
<P>
Hain said Coghlan allegedly owned a warehouse in Gaborone where
fuel and other supplies for UNITA were stored until they could be
flown to rebel camps in Angola.
</P>
<P>
Coghlan, who came to Botswana in 1978 and owns a road transport
and air charter company, has denied the allegations and threatened
to sue the British government for tarnishing his name.
</P>
<P>
"I have no dealing with UNITA and none whatsoever," Coghlan
said.
</P>
<P>
Coghlan claimed that there are many UNITA activists in southern
African countries and they are selling illicit diamonds for
weapons.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations in 1993 banned sales of arms, military
equipment and fuel to UNITA, which has been at war with the
Angolan government since 1975.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions were extended in 1997 to finance, travel and the
diamond trade. 
