<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Beefs Up Fire Fighting Operations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By Zhao Yi
</P>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia is beefing up effort
to put out wildfire in the Borena region bordering with Kenya, a
senior official of the Ministry of Agriculture said here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Two helicopters from the Ethiopian airforce and a spotter plane
offered by South Africa have begun reinforcing the ground fire
fighters in the Borena region where wild fires have been raging
since mid February, Tamirue Habte, spokesperson of the fire
fighting campaign, told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The reinforcement was made possible after the forest fires in
most places of the Bale region, some 400 kilometers south of the
capital Addis Ababa, were extinguished, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia started aerial fire fighting operation about two weeks
ago in the Bale region where a national natural reserve is
situated in.
</P>
<P>
"Two Ethiopian helicopters and one South African spotter plan
have been involved in the battle against the bush fire from 6:00
am to 6:00 pm," Tamirue said.
</P>
<P>
The South African spotter plan is used for locating fire spots
and commanding the anti-fire operation in the air.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, tens of thousands of fire fighters
in the Borena region have been trying to put out the wild fire
with nothing but rakes, beaters and backpack water pumpers.
</P>
<P>
"We have been expecting more effective fire fighting tools from
the world community to put out the conflagration," Tamirue said.
</P>
<P>
Currently, in response to Ethiopia's appeal, South Africa,
Germany, the United States and Canada have either sent their fire
fighters and experts or fire fighting tools to the fire spots.
</P>
<P>
Referring to losses caused by the wild fires, Tamirue said
that Ethiopia had never experienced such big forest fire.
</P>
<P>
"We are mapping extent of the damage," he said. However, he
indicated that it would be difficult to make assessment of
ecological and psychological losses resulted from the wild fire
even if commercial ones were assessed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
