<HEADLINE> Rwandan Parliament Accepts President Bizimungu's Resignation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Rwandan Parliament accepted the
resignation of President Pasteur Bizimungu at an extraordinary
session on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to Rwanda News Agency report, 56 of 59
parliamentarians present at the meeting approved the president
resignation.
</P>
<P>
"I have resigned my post on March 23, 2000, as the President of
the Republic of Rwanda for my personal reasons," Bizimungu said in
his letter to the Speaker of the National Transitional Assembly.
</P>
<P>
In another letter to the Vice President of Rwanda and chairman
of the Rwandan Patriotic Front (RPF), Paul Kagame, Bizimungu said,
 "I have resigned from the leadership of the party as the vice
chairman and member of the National Executive Committee and the
Political Bureau.
</P>
<P>
I tried my best to serve the movement (RPF) and the nation; I
therefore apologize for any mistake. I will continue to serve the
nation and the movement as an ordinary RPF member."
</P>
<P>
Bizimungu quit his post after accusing members of parliament of
having played a crucial role in the resignation of the former
Prime Minister Pierre Celestin Rwigema and other cabinet ministers
for allegedly involving in corruption.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the parliament on Monday, Bizimungu said that
parliamentarians violated constitutional provisions by summoning
several members of the cabinet on charges of corruption committed
before the organic law that empowers parliament to control
government was passed.
</P>
<P>
According to an RPF official, Bizimungu threatened to resign
for the first time in last December, following the complaints by
Masaka residents in Kigali rural prefecture that they had been
illegally displaced by President Bizimungu in order to get enough
grazing land.
</P>
<P>
After RPF received a letter from Masaka residents calling for
protection of their rights, three RPF members were sent to the
President to settle the matter. The President was annoyed by the
act and threatened to resign. Top RPF leaders convinced him not to
do so.
</P>
<P>
According to the Arusha peace accord, the Speaker of the
National Transitional Assembly assumes the interim presidency
after the resignation of the President, and the parliament and
cabinet members will elect the new President from the two
candidates nominated by the RPF. 
</P>
</TEXT>
