<HEADLINE> Finally a "Family Photo" of EU Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LISBON, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Finally, a "family photo" of
European Union heads of state and government was taken Thursday,
but only with someone outside the 15-nation bloc making them line
up in front of camera lenses.
</P>
<P>
A family photo of EU heads of state and government is usual for
any of the union's special summits. But one had been deemed so
difficult for the Lisbon version of the special council in that
Austria's 14 EU partners have been boycotting the country
politically.
</P>
<P>
French President Jacques Chirac, one of the two presidents
attending the two-day summit Thursday and Friday in Lisbon, agreed
to take his place for a group photo of European Union leaders with
visiting Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo on the margins of the
summit.
</P>
<P>
France and Belgium have been cold-shouldering Austria ever
since the coalition government with Joerg Haider's far-right
Freedom Party swore into office in Austria on February 6.
</P>
<P>
Chirac earlier announced that he would stay away from the
traditional family photo with Austrian Prime Minister Wolfgang
Schuessel as continued protest against Vienna's coalition
government.
</P>
<P>
Belgian Prime Minister Guy Verhofstadt, who had also planned to
boycott the family photo, agreed to the arrangement by Portugal,
that is now holding the six-month rotating presidency of the 15-
nation bloc.
</P>
<P>
Schuessel had asked the gathering of EU leaders to lift the
political ban on his country and hoped that the Lisbon summit
would mark the start of normalized relations between Vienna and
other EU capitals.
</P>
<P>
"I will explain our position and I hope that the path to
normalization can begin here," said Schuessel. "I don't expect a
final solution but I think that with my message a path toward
normalization will be opened during the next weeks and months."
</P>
<P>
Portuguese opposition leader Jose Manuel Durao Barroso told the
Austrian prime minister that he would do everything he could to
resolve the "lamentable" divisions in Europe's conservative
political family over Vienna's coalition with Haider's ultra-right
Freedom Party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
