<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Urges Council to View DDR as One Part of Peacekeeping Operations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 23 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Thursday urged the Security Council to view disarmament,
demobilization and reintegration (DDR) as only one part of the
multifaceted approach in peacekeeping operations.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the open debate of the Security Council on the role
of U.N. peacekeeping in disarmament, demobilization and
reintegration, Annan said today's peacekeeping operations bears
little resemblance to its original character, they seek not only
to bring stability to areas of conflict, but also to address the
root causes of conflict.
</P>
<P>
"If peacekeeping operations are supporting DDR processes
efficiently, it is essential that provisions for DDR be integrated
into any peace agreement that is reached," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
"The arrangements for disposal of arms and ammunition should be
decided as part of peace negotiations, so that the question of
what to do with the collected arms and ammunition does not
subsequently become a stumbling block," the U.N. chief said.
</P>
<P>
"It is also often essential that arms issues be considered in a
regional context. Prerequisites for a successful regional approach
include bilateral decisions to share intelligence and information,
cooperation by relevant regional organizations and continued
support from the Security Council," he said.
</P>
<P>
Annan said responding to arms trafficking may also require a
focus on financial flows, including information in where faction
leaders are obtaining funds, where they are holding them and how
they are spending them.
</P>
<P>
"Primary responsibility for reintegration falls outside
peacekeeping. I believe that peacekeeping operations can
nonetheless play a key role in this important element of post-
conflict reconstruction," the U.N. chief added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000323.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seoul Regards DPRK's Breach of Disputed Sea Line As Provocation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, March 23 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean Navy said Thursday
it will regard the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK)
vessels' entry into the Northern Limit Line (NLL) as a provocation.
</P>
<P>
If the DPRK Navy violates the NLL in the name of its rules on
access to the five -islands, "our armed forces will consider it a
provocation and will not tolerate it", the South Korean Navy said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
As an apparent response to the DPRK Navy's announcement of six-
point rules restricting sea and air access to five islands in the
Yellow Sea, the South Korean Navy said the NLL is the practical
sea border line.
</P>
<P>
Not only the NLL has been maintained as the sea demarcation
line separating the South from the North since 1953 but it was
also provided for under the basic inter-Korean agreement concluded
in 1992, said the navy.
</P>
<P>
This position of the South Korean Navy was explicitly
manifested in a statement the South Korean Joint Chiefs of Staff
issued on September 3, 1999, the navy added.
</P>
<P>
The 1953 armistice that ended the Korean War did not demarcate
a sea border, often raising sovereignty disputes between the two
Koreas. The five islands -- Paekryong, Taechong, Sochong, Yonpyong
and Woo -- are scattered over 90 kilometers along the loosely
designated sea border off the west coast of the Korean Peninsula,
and they are situated closer to the DPRK side.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK People's Army General Staff unilaterally declared last
September its drawn demarcation line in the Yellow Sea, but the
South Korea refused it.
</P>
<P>
On June 15 last year, an inter-Korean military conflict
occurred in the NLL drawn in 1953 by the United States, with a
DPRK torpedo boat hit and sunken by South Korea.
</P>
<P>
Pyongyang has never recognized the NLL since it was drawn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000323.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Secret Service Attacks Officer Returned From Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A clash took place between Colonel Jean-Michel Mechain and
eight agents of the protection and security section (DPSD) of the
Defense Ministry when the former was followed on a street in the
20th district in eastern Paris.
</P>
<P>
Colonel Mechain was sent to hospital after being slightly
injured by the DPSD agents, Agence France-Presse quoted police
sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The DPSD is in charge of protection and security for "sensitive
personnel, information, materials and installations" and
investigating any leakage of secret information about them.
</P>
<P>
The French Defense Ministry has refused to comment on the
incident.
</P>
<P>
The French weekly Le Point and the popular newspaper Le Canard
published in February the extracts from a secret report by French
troops serving in the multinational force in Kosovo (KFOR), which
said that French military officers in Kosovo were angry with the U.
N. Civil Administrator in Kosovo, Bernard Kouchner, who held a pro-
Albanian stand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
