<DOCNO> XIE20000323.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan, U.S. Fail to Make Breakthrough in Talks on NTT Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Japan and the United States ended
three days of high-level deregulation talks Thursday, failing to
narrow their differences over the size of planned cuts in
interconnection fees charged by Nippon Telegraph and Telephone
Corp. (NTT).
</P>
<P>
"I was briefed that the talks ended in failure because of
considerable gaps" over the telecom issue, Japanese Chief Cabinet
Secretary Mikio Aoki told a regular press conference.
</P>
<P>
During the three-day talks, Japan made a concession by
expressing its readiness to accelerate its plan to cut the
interconnection fees that NTT charges its competitors to access
the NTT's local circuits by 22.5 percent over four years, Japanese
officials said.
</P>
<P>
The concession, however, did not satisfy the U.S., which has
been calling for a deeper cut.
</P>
<P>
Deputy U.S. Trade Representative Richard Fisher told a press
conference after the talks that Japan "is proposing a policy that
would reduce the costs by too little over too long a period."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. initially demanded an immediate 50 percent cut, but it
is now willing to allow Japan several years to cut the rate by
half.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. side reportedly made a new proposal at the latest
talks, calling for a 22.5 percent cut in access charges over two
years and a more than 40 percent reduction thereafter.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Washington maintained that the NTT should be
able to achieve the reduction the U.S. is seeking through
streamlining efforts by NTT group companies, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
But Tokyo would not agree to the cuts proposed by the U.S.,
saying such cuts would likely accompany hikes of basic charges
that the NTT levies on its subscribers.
</P>
<P>
Tokyo is also concerned that a sharp cut in interconnection
fees would affect the NTT's profits, resulting in cuts in the NTT'
s workforce.
</P>
<P>
Due to the failure to resolve the issue, Tokyo and Washington
may not be able to compile an updated bilateral deregulation
report by the March 31 deadline.
</P>
<P>
The issue may also develop into a major trade row between the
two countries ahead of the annual summit of the Group of Eight (G-
8) major countries to be held from July 21 to 23 in Okinawa
Prefecture, as Washington has expressed its intention to raise the
issue in the political arena, the officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000323.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Population Growth Hits Record Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Japan's population stood at 126.68
million as of October 1 last year, up 200,000, or 0.16 percent
from a year earlier, the lowest increase since the end of World
War II, the Management and Coordination Agency said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The total, 126,686,000, consisted of 64,714,000 women and 61,
972,000 men, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Of Japan's 47 prefectures, Okinawa had the highest rate of
increase, while 23 prefectures, including Osaka and Kyoto, saw
their populations declining, with Akita Prefecture posting the
biggest decline in its population, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
With the rapid aging of Japan's population, the number of
people aged 65 or over totaled 21.18 million, up 679,000 from a
year earlier. The number accounts for 16.7 percent of the
population, compared with 16.2 percent as of October 1, 1998, the
agency said.
</P>
<P>
The number of children under 14 dropped 316,000 to 18.74
million, accounting for only 14.8 percent of the population. It
was the first time that the number fell below 15 percent, the
agency added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
