<DOCNO> XIE20000323.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Combat Tuberculosis: Senior Health Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Tuberculosis claims 250,000 lives
each year in China, and is thus a major public health problem
hindering the country's social and economic development, according
to a senior Chinese health official.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Minister of Health Yin Dakui said here today a total of
six million tuberculosis (TB) patients make China the second
largest country in the world in terms of TB population, next only
to India.
</P>
<P>
Without effective measures, about 200 million to 300 million
healthy Chinese might be infected by tubercle bacillus in the next
decade, and one tenth of them might become TB patients, Yin warned
at a symposium on World TB Day, which falls tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
The country's health care system is also confronted with other
TB-related issues, such as higher TB incidence in rural areas,
greater risk of a TB epidemic associated with HIV/AIDS, and drug
resistance cases as a result of irregular treatment.
</P>
<P>
Yin said that China suffers serious loss of work force each
year owing to the infectious disease, because 75 percent of TB
patients are between 15 and 54 years old.
</P>
<P>
"We plan to work out medium and long-term plans for TB control
for the coming decade on the basis of a national epidemiological
survey to be completed this year," he said.
</P>
<P>
Effective treatment recommended by the World Health
Organization will be introduced to more areas to curb the spread
of TB, he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000323.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Allows Import of US Wheat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 23 (Xinhua) -- So long as its own wheat industry
is not threatened, China allows the import of all kinds of wheat
from the United States, according to a government bulletin
published today.
</P>
<P>
The bulletin was issued in accordance with a Sino-U.S.
agreement on agricultural cooperation by the Chinese Ministry of
Agriculture, the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation and the State Administration of Inspection of Import
and Export Commodities.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. quarantine departments should inspect and quarantine
the wheat which is to be exported to China and should provide
quarantine certificates for the qualified batches, according to
the bulletin.
</P>
<P>
The number of TCK spores in wheat imported from the US should
not surpass the number written in the Sino-US agreement, and
relevant research on TCK spores will be carried out between the
two countries to make the calculation of the number of such spores
more accurate, the bulletin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
