<DOCNO> XIE20000323.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Economy Experiencing Third Turning Point: Tung </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong Chief Executive Tung
Chee Hwa said Thursday that Hong Kong was coming precisely across
the "third strategic inflection point" in its economic history,
referring to the knowledge-based economy.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong was indeed facing a new major challenge now, and to
manage this change, "we should harness the potential of technology
to add value to our economic activities, and particularly
information technology, which holds the key to our future," Tung
said at the 40th anniversary dinner of the Federation of Hong Kong
Industries.
</P>
<P>
He urged businesses to reflect deeply on their established
business model, saying that "we need to be able to make productive
application of technology to add value to our businesses and to
make ourselves more competitive in the global business environment.
"
</P>
<P>
"This is not just for industries and big companies that can
obviously benefit from technology, but also in many of the more
traditional lines of business and medium and even small companies
as well," he said.
</P>
<P>
He was confident that Hong Kong industries would be able to
continue to respond effectively through the market and that their
shrewd business sense would help Hong Kong meet new challenges and
scale new heights.
</P>
<P>
Quoting British historian Arnold Toynbee's saying that "
civilizations rise or fall depending on whether they are able to
give the right responses to challenges under demanding conditions",
Tung said "this situation of challenge and response is clearly
where we, and in fact our competitors, are today."
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong passed the first historical strategic inflection
point when its role as an entrepot to the Chinese Mainland
diminished in the 1950s. The second strategic inflection point was
passed in the late 1970s when land and labor costs became major
constraints for Hong Kong industries. Expansion of industrial base
into Southern China solved these problems.
</P>
<P>
Tung stressed that the government was committed to providing
the necessary support to industry to help them meet the challenges,
such as the 5 billion HKD (640,000 USD) Innovation and Technology
Fund and the Science Park, which had signed up three international
technology companies already.
</P>
<P>
"In the next few weeks, I am going to announce the appointments
to the Council of Advisers on Innovation and Technology and to the
Board of Directors of the Applied Science and Technology Institute,
" he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
