<DOCNO> XIE20000323.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Fears No U.S.-Iranian Rapprochement: Aziz </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Iraq's Deputy Prime Minister Tareq
Aziz stressed Thursday that Iraq does not fear any rapprochement
between the U.S., its arch enemy, and Iran, a long-term hostile
neighbor.
</P>
<P>
The real purpose of the U.S. decision to improve relations with
Iran, said Aziz in an interview with Monte Carlo radio, is to
prolong the war between Iran and Iraq, aiming to cause more damage
to both countries.
</P>
<P>
Aziz called upon Iranian leaders not to be misled by the U.S.
scheme. Iraq and Iran fought for eight years in the 1980s before
reaching a ceasefire in 1988. About 1 million people from both
sides lost their lives.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi official was referring to remarks made by U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who regretted U.S. support
for Iraq in the Iran-Iraq war as "shortsighted"
</P>
<P>
Aziz accused Albright of being "specialized at distorting facts
and telling lies." It has been known to all that the U.S. sold arms
to Iran in the so-called Irangate scandal, but nobody knows when
the U.S. supported Iraq against Iran, he said.
</P>
<P>
In a speech to the American-Iranian Council in Washington last
Friday, Albright announced the U.S. would ease sanctions against
Iran, allowing the purchase and import of Iran's goods such as
carpet, dried fruits, nuts and caviar. This move was seen as the
boldest attempt yet by the Clinton Administration to try to improve
relations with Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Iran has welcomed the move as "positive" and said that Tehran
would respond by importing U.S. grain and medicine.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Iran severed relations in 1980 following the
takeover of the U.S. embassy in Tehran by fervent Iranian students
in the heydays of the Islamic revolution, which toppled the former
pro-U.S. shah's regime.
</P>
<P>
The two countries tuned down their hostilities against each
other after President Mohammad Khatami, who came to power in 1997,
called for people-to-people contacts to bring down the "wall of
mistrust".
</P>
<P>
Relations between Iran and Iraq have remained strained. More
than a decade after the end of the war, they have yet to settle
issues related to prisoners of war, border demarcation and
reparations.
</P>
<P>
For years, the two Gulf neighbors have been trading accusations
against each other for harboring dissidents who are engaged in
terrorist activities, hampering the normalization of bilateral
relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
