<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan not Backing Terrorism: Musharraf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Chief Executive
General Pervez Musharraf Thursday said that his government had
never been involved in terrorism in the Indian-controlled Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
He made this remark during his press conference here when his
reaction was sought on U.S. President Bill Clinton's statement on
violence in the Indian-controlled Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, who is visit India currently, in an recent interview
had said, "I believe that there are elements within the Pakistani
government that have supported those who engaged in violence in
Kashmir."
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, General Musharraf condemned the killing of 35
Sikhs in Indian-controlled Kashmir and demanded "high level
inquiry" into the incident so that India could not exploit it for
"a propaganda purpose".
</P>
<P>
He said there are strong evidences that Indian security
officials were "directly involved in the killing." "It might be a
move by India to divert world attention from the Indian repression
in occupied Kashmir," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Unidentified gunmen killed 35 Sikhs in a village in India-
controlled Kashmir on Monday night, just hours before Clinton's
visit to India. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
