<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Barrier in Science Flow Between India, U.S.:  Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Science should not be imprisoned. There should be no barriers
in flow of science and technology," said Joshi during his meeting
here with the scientists, who are accompanying visiting U.S.
President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
India and the United States signed an agreement here on Tuesday
on the establishment of an Indo-U.S. Science and Technology Forum,
which aims at promoting collaboration and exchanges between the
two countries in the field of science and technology.
</P>
<P>
Describing the Forum as a "fresh chapter" in science
collaboration between the two countries, Joshi said it would also
provide an independent platform to discuss thorny issues such as
the removal of technology sanctions imposed against India
following the country's nuclear tests in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Joshi also discussed with the U.S. scientists the potential for
collaboration in information technology, climate, clean energy and
ocean studies. The Indian side also expressed interest in
collaboration in the computer hardware sector.
</P>
<P>
Also on Thursday, a non-governmental organization based in New
Delhi strongly criticized an Indo-U.S. pact on clean energy and
environment signed on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the pact, the United States will provide an
assistance of 45 million U.S. dollars for India to develop clean
energy and water projects.
</P>
<P>
The Center for Science and Environment (CSE) criticized that
the pact would compel India to buy U.S. technology, which would
provide extra business for U.S. companies.
</P>
<P>
"What they (the Americans) are saying effectively is to take a
little bit of money from us, buy our more efficient technology,
but we will take the credit for greenhouse gas reduction," said
the CSE in a statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
