<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India, Australia To Resume Defense Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It was also decided to further consolidate bilateral ties
between New Delhi and Canberra during a meeting between Indian
External Affairs Minister Jaswant Singh and Australian Foreign
Minister Alexander Downer, who arrived here today for a two-day
visit.
</P>
<P>
Details would be worked out by respective defense ministries, a
spokesman of the Indian External Affairs Ministry told the media
here.
</P>
<P>
Following India's nuclear tests, Australia took a tough stand
and withdrawn its defense attache from its high commission here
and cut-off all defense ties with New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
During their meeting today, the two ministers felt that Indo-
Australian relations should not be constrained by any single issue,
the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Downer reiterated Canberra's position that India should sign
the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT) while appreciated that
New Delhi was moving ahead on development a national consensus on
the issue, he added.
</P>
<P>
Singh described Indo-Australian relations as an account of "
unfulfilled potential", saying it was time for the two countries
to rediscover their connectivities.
</P>
<P>
Singh briefed his counterpart on the on-going visit by U.S.
President Bill Clinton and his talks with Indian leader including
Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee, the spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
