<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WFP Launches Food Aid Program in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 23 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. World Food Program (WFP)
will spend 50 million U.S. dollars on food aid to hundreds of
thousands of people living in precarious circumstances in northern
Uganda in the next two years.
</P>
<P>
The agency made the announcement in Kenya's capital Nairobi
Thursday at a crucial time as violent attacks by rebel groups in
the northern part of Uganda continued unabated.
</P>
<P>
Tens of thousands of Ugandans have been forced out of their
homes and many of them have sought shelters and protection in
ad-hoc camps near urban centers, WFP said in a news release.
</P>
<P>
"We are doing everything possible to ensure that food aid
continues to reach these people whose lives have been devastated
by senseless violence," said Burk Oberle, WFP Regional Manager for
the Great Lakes region.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, an attack on Padibe camp, which were
hosting 30,000 internally displaced people and is 25 kilometers
north of Kitgum town, killed 12 people and injured 40 others,
with 400 homes burnt to the ground.
</P>
<P>
The violence is believed to have been carried out by the
Lord's Resistance Army, a fundamentalist rebel group that has been
operating in the region for the past 13 years.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. agency said it is currently feeding over 550,000
displaced people in Uganda, nearly 80 percent of them are living
in the north of the country and the remainders are based in the
southwestern district of Bundibudgyo.
</P>
<P>
In addition to providing emergency assistance, WFP will focus
on setting up food-for-work and training programs in Uganda over
the next two years.
</P>
<P>
These projects will give those displaced by violence and the
communities vulnerable to food shortage the skills and
opportunities to enhance their agricultural production and
economic development, the agency said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
