<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda to Probe Cult Mass Suicide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By Feng Jian
</P>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
has said that the government would set up a special commission of
inquiry to look into the March 17 mass suicide by cult members.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference at the State House here Thursday
afternoon, the president said the commission would have to submit
a comprehensive report on the matter within six months.
</P>
<P>
The government would, based on this report, work out plans to
restrict and uproot all cults endangering people's lives. he said.
</P>
<P>
When asked about the reasons for the existence of the cult
Movement for the Restoration of Ten Commandments of God in Uganda,
Museveni attributed it to lack of education and unemployment.
</P>
<P>
"Lack of education and unemployment make it possible for the
illiterate people in the rural areas to resort to cults when they
are sick," the president told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the importance of economic development, especially
the industrialization process to Uganda, saying that this is the
only way to eliminate cults and cult activities from the country.
</P>
<P>
Some preventive measures would be taken in the short run and
security organs have been directed to arrest the cult leaders if
they are alive and still on the run, he said.
</P>
<P>
At the function, Internal Affairs Minister Edward Rugumayo said
that a report by forensic experts would be ready on Thursday and
it would help establish the nature of the incident in which 530
people, including 78 children, died. 
</P>
</TEXT>
