<HEADLINE> Ugandans Urged to Donate More Aid to Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Ugandans have been urged to
donate more fund to the Mozambicans who have been affected by the
recent devastating floods and are still living under threats of
more floods.
</P>
<P>
The call was made by Uganda National Commission of PanAfrican
Movement here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Jimmy Dean, chairman of the national commission, told reporters
in the Ministry of Foreign Affairs that his organization has
opened a bank account in Kampala to receive donations from
individuals or associations.
</P>
<P>
"On the first day of opening the account, we receive some
500,000 shillings (over 300 U.S. dollars) and more money is coming
in. We just want to lobby more support and send the fund to our
brothers in need in Mozambique," said Kintu Nyago, a prominent
member of the movement.
</P>
<P>
The movement appealed to the media to play a better role in
soliciting support for those affected by floods.
</P>
<P>
The National Commission of PanAfrican Movement was set up in
1994 and it has organized workshops, conferences and debates on
various topics and offered training courses.
</P>
<P>
The flooding in Mozambique has left tens of thousands of people
homeless and lack of basic medical services. Food reliefs and
other forms of support have poured into the country to help it
recover from the disaster. 
</P>
</TEXT>
