<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seoul Dismisses Pyongyang's Rules on Voyage to 5 Islands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, March 23 (Xinhua) -- South Korea decided Thursday
evening to dismiss Pyongyang's latest rules on sea and air access
to five islands in the Yellow Sea.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean decision was made at a working-level meeting
of the Defense Ministry, which said it will maintain by all means
the Northern Limit Line (NLL) as provided for under the basic
inter-Korean agreement.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Thursday, the Navy of the Democratic People's Republic
of Korea (DPRK) announced a six-point order of the five islands in
the Yellow Sea.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK Navy said if and when U.S. and South Korean military
and private vessels swerve from the designated routes, it would be
believed as an act to violate the DPRK's territorial waters and
sky.
</P>
<P>
The NLL was made in 1953 by the United States after the Korean
War and the DPRK is not allowed entry into disputed waters, but
Pyongyang has never accepted.
</P>
<P>
The disputed waters good for crab fishing saw an inter-Korean
naval battle during the crab-fishing season last June, in which a
DPRK torpedo boat was sunken.
</P>
<P>
Last September, the DPRK unilaterally announced its drawn sea
demarcation line south of the NLL.
</P>
<P>
The five islands are south of the NLL but north of the DPRK's
sea demarcation line.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean ministry viewed the DPRK Navy's announcement
of the order as a "plot to cause social chaos" in South Korea
before the April 13 general elections and the crab-fishing season
for South Korean fishermen in the disputed waters.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said it "will not take any immediate military
countermeasures" but will keep a sharp eye on the DPRK's naval
movements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
