<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Observing Nuke Test Moratorium: Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 23 (Xinhua) -- The United States is observing the
moratorium on nuclear tests in compliance with the Comprehensive
Test Ban Treaty (CTBT), a source in the Atomic Ministry press
service said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The source, quoted by the Interfax news agency, was commenting
on western media reports about an underground test in Nevada and
an ensuing demonstration of protest in the Japanese city of
Hiroshima.
</P>
<P>
"By all appearances, this was a non-nuclear explosion. As we
know, the U.S. is observing the test moratorium, which they
announced in September 1992. The work under way in Nevada does not
violate the CTBT because no nuclear energy is emitted in that kind
of test," he said.
</P>
<P>
The official said that Russia, which is also observing a test
ban, carries out non-nuclear explosions too, adding, "their
primary aim is to ensure the safety of the nuclear stockpile which
is being used."
</P>
<P>
Russia conducted its latest non-nuclear explosion in the
northern Novaya Zemlya island in January 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
