<HEADLINE> South China Plans Blitz on Tax Dodging </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANTOU, March 23 (Xinhua) -- The national tax officers in the
Chaoshan area of south China's Guangdong Province vowed here today
to crack down on local tax dodging.
</P>
<P>
Located on the coast, the Chaoshan area includes the cities of
Chaozhou, Shantou, Shanwei and Jieyang, where there is a thriving
market economy. But tax dodging is rife due to lax supervision.
</P>
<P>
The State Administration of Taxation issued a notice at the
beginning of this year to strengthen tax work in the area.
</P>
<P>
The Guangdong Provincial State Taxation Bureau has sent a group
to the Chaoshan area to help the work. Chen Liuming, director of
the bureau, called for effective measures to stop tax cheating.
</P>
<P>
He asked the officers to sort out and verify all ordinary value-
added taxpayers and weed out illegal manufacturers and those
issuing illegal value-added tax invoices.
</P>
<P>
He revealed that a computer software program would soon be in
operation to help the effort.  
</P>
</TEXT>
