<DOCNO> XIE20000323.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Signs Aviation Agreements with 3 Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Under an agreement signed with the government of Thailand, it
was decided that designated airlines of both countries would be
entitled to operate a maximum of 4,100 seats per week in each
direction with any type of aircraft instead of eight frequencies
per week, said the release.
</P>
<P>
The designated airline of Thailand has also been permitted to
operate services to Mumbai under a code share and block space
arrangement with Air India, it added.
</P>
<P>
Under the Air Services Agreement between India and Sri Lanka,
it was agreed that the designated airline of Sri Lanka may
increase the capacity deployment on the specified routes by 745
seats per week in each direction by using the unutilized
entitlement of Indian carriers, said the release.
</P>
<P>
The designated airline of Sri Lanka was also granted Calcutta
and Varanasi as new points in India, it said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the release said, delegations of the Indian
government and the government of Turkmenistan, following a meeting
here, also agreed that Amritsar would be included as an additional
point in India for the designated airline of Turkmenistan.
</P>
<P>
The capacity entitlement of either side was revised from 400
seats per week to 900 seats per week in a phased manner, the
release added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
