<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> TB Kills 60,000 in Bangladesh Every Year: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Tuberculosis (TB) remains a major
killer disease in Bangladesh, silently killing over 60,000 people
every year owing to poverty and people's ignorance of the health
hazard, said a United Nations Children's Fund report released
Thursday on the occasion of World Tuberculosis Day on March 24.
</P>
<P>
"One in every 10 minutes dies of TB in Bangladesh, while one in
every 2 minutes get infected," said the report. In 1997,
Bangladesh accounted for 3.6 percent of the TB cases worldwide.
</P>
<P>
TB kills over 60,000 people in the country every year, the
report said, branding Bangladesh as the worst TB-affected country
in South Asia and the fourth worst-affected in the world.
</P>
<P>
According to recent estimates, there are 600,000 existing cases
of TB, with 300,000 new cases reported every year in Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
"The frightening state calls for comprehensive measures to
control TB in Bangladesh, which is a priority for the country and
even for the world," said the U.N. agency.
</P>
<P>
Tuberculosis and its causes are closely linked to poverty. The
probability of becoming infected and developing clinical
conditions is associated with malnutrition, crowding, poor air
circulation, and poor sanitation.
</P>
<P>
Recent medical reports indicated that TB and HIV/AIDS support
and host each other, and when TB is correctly treated, the
incidence of HIV/AIDS is also automatically reduced.
</P>
<P>
Bangladeshi Health and Family Welfare Minister Sheikh Fazlul
Karim Selim Thursday urged upon the world community to come
forward in combating TB and sought coordinated efforts of
development partners for overcoming the disease at a three-day
ministerial conference on "Tuberculosis and Sustainable
Development" held in Amsterdam, Holland.
</P>
<P>
National Tuberculosis Control program of Bangladesh has adopted
the Directly Observed Treatment Short-course method. Diagnosis and
treatment services are available in all health complexes free of
cost. 
</P>
