<HEADLINE> Clinton's Visit to Bangladesh Opens Up New Vistas  for Bilateral Cooperation: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 23 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Clinton's just-
concluded visit to Bangladesh has opened up new vistas for
bilateral cooperation and raised the image and stature of
Bangladesh "immensely" in international relations, Foreign
Secretary C.M. Shafi Sami said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Briefing newsmen on the outcome of the "historic visit" by
President Clinton, Shafi Sami said it was a "clear and positive
recognition" by the United States of the constructive and forward-
looking policies of the present government.
</P>
<P>
He said now that the visit is over, "the world community will,
no doubt, assess the visit from the importance that the United
States has attached to Bangladesh."
</P>
<P>
Referring to the invitation extended to Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina by President Clinton to visit the United States, Sami said
when materialized, Hasina's visit, expected to take place in
October, will be the "first official visit by a Bangladesh leader
on an invitation extended by a U.S. President in person."
</P>
<P>
On the question of raising ready-made garment export quota,
giving duty-free access of Bangladeshi goods to the U.S. market
and supporting Bangladeshi information technology industry, the
foreign secretary said Bangladesh received encouraging response
from the Americans in these fields.
</P>
<P>
The issue of regularizing undocumented Bangladeshis living in
the United States and deportation of the killers of Mujibur Rahman,
the first prime minister of Bangladesh, also received sympathetic
response from the U.S. president, he added. 
</P>
