<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia's Chief of General Staff to Visit NATO Headquarters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MOSCOW, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Russia's Chief of General Staff
Anatoly Kvashnin will visit NATO headquarters in Brussels in May
to discuss the situation in Kosovo, a top Defense Ministry
official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Kvashnin is expected to arrive in Brussels on May 10, when the
Council of NATO Chiefs of Staff convene, Leonid Ivashov, head of
the Defense Ministry's International Military Cooperation
Department, was quoted by Interfax as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The main issue Kvashnin is expected to raise in Brussels is
the situation in Kosovo," Ivashov said.
</P>
<P>
He said the Russian Defense Ministry considers the current
situation favorable for cooperation between Russia and NATO.
</P>
<P>
"What NATO is on March 23, 2000, is much better than what it
was on March 24, 1999."
</P>
<P>
NATO launched massive air strikes against Yugoslavia on March
24, 1999, prompting Moscow to freeze all military ties with the
alliance.
</P>
<P>
Russia's latest contacts with NATO have demonstrated that not
everything is that simple with NATO, although on the whole Russia
is being increasingly involved in the European security process,
Ivashov said.
</P>
<P>
"We could not have dismissed this chance for 'unfreezing'
relations with the alliance," he said, adding that "further
relations with NATO will largely depend on NATO itself."
</P>
<P>
In contrast to his positive comments on Russia-NATO ties,
Ivashov Wednesday played down the thawing of relations between the
two sides.
</P>
<P>
He insisted that the two sides are only "at the beginning of
the path" toward the full restoration of relations and that
promotion of the relations depends on NATO's readiness for a
dialogue with Russia on equal terms.
</P>
<P>
Ivashov also said it is premature to talk about opening any
NATO mission in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
"The time has not yet come to open a NATO military
communications mission and information office in Moscow."
</P>
<P>
Russia's acting President Vladimir Putin caused a stir when he
indicated in an interview with BBC television earlier this month
that Russia could join NATO if Moscow were treated as an equal
partner. But Moscow then backtracked by saying that Putin was
speaking on hypothetical basis.
</P>
<P>
Ivashov announced Thursday that Russia is considering the
possibility of setting up a base for the repair and maintenance of
the Russian military equipment used in the Kosovo peacekeeping
operation. But he added that "there are no plans for setting up a
Russian military base in Kosovo."
</P>
<P>
"If this issue ever does come up, it will be handled by Moscow
and Belgrade on a bilateral basis with due account taken of
international norms and principles," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
