<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Newcastle United Replace Chief Executive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 23 (Xinhua) -- English premier league soccer club
Newcastle United sacked chief executive Freddie Fletcher on
Thursday with the finance director for north-east rivals
Sunderland taking the position.
</P>
<P>
David Stonehouse will take over on April 3 after the latest
boardroom ruction at the premier league club.
</P>
<P>
According to the Reuters report, Fletcher assumed Newcastle's
executive chairman duties after the acrimonious resignation of the
club's chairman in December 1998 and two months ago a board
restructuring left him to focus on media rights and new business
development.
</P>
<P>
His surprise departure may be linked to fan power after this
month's bitter court battle with supporters over Newcastle's plans
to move them from their regular seats to make way for a corporate
hospitality area.
</P>
<P>
Newcastle have dragged themselves from the bottom of the league
since Bobby Robson took over as manager from Ruud Gullit, who
resigned in August.
</P>
<P>
But scars still remain from the furore surrounding directors
Douglas Hall and Freddy Shepherd after they made disparaging
remarks about fans in early 1998.
</P>
<P>
Hall and Shepherd, who control a majority of the company's
shares, resigned as directors in March 1998.
</P>
<P>
But Denis Cassidy quit as Newcastle chairman in December 1998
along with two fellow executives after Hall and Shepherd were
restored to the board. The company's stockbrokers resigned at the
same stage.
</P>
<P>
Sunderland Plc said in due course it would appoint a
replacement for Stonehouse, who joined in 1996 and was involved in
bringing Sunderland to flotation on London's Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
Sunderland have enjoyed a good season after being promoted to
the premier league and are currently in eighth place, ahead of
Newcastle in 11th.
</P>
<P>
Newcastle also said on Thursday that Les Wheatley, chief
operating officer and finance director, had resigned and would
take up the position of finance director at Liverpool.
</P>
<P>
Cable company NTL announced in December it had taken a 9.8
percent stake in Newcastle after giving the club a 25 million
pound (39.43 million dollars) cash injection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
