<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Faces Severe Water Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus is confronting a severe
water shortage as state reservoirs are nearly 85 percent empty with
only 40 million cubic meters of water behind the dams, local media
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
With the drought in its fifth straight year, Cyprus has urged an
complete of the Larnaca desalination plant, at the southern coast
of the island, by December this year, four months earlier than the
original date set in the contract with Israel, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus will pay more money in return, it added.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the Cyprus government is trying to make the Dhekelia
desalination plant at Cyprus' southeast coast, currently the
island's sole such facility, desalt an extra 10,000 to 20,000 cubic
metres of water a day.
</P>
<P>
The Dhekelia plant, currently operating at maximum output,
desalts 40,000 cubic metres of water daily.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the government is considering a Greek offer to ship
free fresh water to Cyprus from Greece.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has got mere 254 millimeters of precipitation since
October 1999, only half of the normal figure in a rainy season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
