<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 23 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- As relations between Turkey and Syria are warming up,
the two neighbors have seen their border trade becoming more
active, Turkish Daily News reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Syrians consider buying goods through Turkey's Sanliurfa,
the nearest city to the Syrian cities of Aleppo, Al Raqqah and Al
Hasakah, much easier and cheaper than importing them from far-off
countries of France and England, said Ismail Demirkol, president of
the Chamber of Trade and Industry of Sanliurfa.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, a Turkish Export Goods Fair is to be
held in Damascus on April 7-11.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkish conglomerate Koc Holding and Dutch logistics
giant TNT Post Group NY have sealed a letter of intent to launch a
joint venture, Turkish Daily News reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The alliance will at first focus its business activities on
automobiles and durable consumption goods and later expand to
express distribution activities and other sectors.
</P>
<P>
The Amsterdam-based TNT Post Group operates in a total of 60
countries and is a market leader in Europe, Australia, North and
South America.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- The World Bank decided on Wednesday to offer Yemen a
grant of 29 million U.S. dollars to help the country implement the
Childhood Development Project.
</P>
<P>
The project is designed to improve the health and food
conditions of children under the age of five, enhance primary
education for women and address the problems of children.
</P>
<P>
The total cost of the project amounts to 45 million dollars,
including 29 million from the World Bank, 12.4 million from the
United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF), 2.4 million from the
Yemeni government and 1.2 million from non-governmental
organizations.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- Yemen and Japan signed here on Wednesday a memorandum
of understanding under which Japan will grant Yemen 4 million U.S.
dollars to improve the health of Yemeni women and children.
</P>
<P>
The money, part of Japan's assistance for the social and
economic development of Yemen, will be used in purchasing medical
equipments to better the gynecological and pediatric services at
eight district hospitals. 
</P>
