<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Economic Growth Targeted For 1.5 Pct </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's economic growth for
the fiscal year 1999/2000 ending on March 31 this year is targeted
to grow by 1.5 percent, higher than previous estimate at zero
percent, the Budget Committee of the House of Representatives
revealed Thursday in a committee plenary session with the Ministry
of Finance.
</P>
<P>
The committee also set the oil price at 19.7 U.S. dollars per
barrel, higher than previous figure at 10.5 U.S. dollars a barrel.
</P>
<P>
It also said that the country's crude oil production during the
current fiscal year is targeted to reach 1.435 million barrel per
day (bpd), decreased from 1.52 million bpd at previous target.
</P>
<P>
"While the rupiah exchange rate against U.S. dollar is targeted
at level 7,454 rupiah per U.S. dollar, from 7,500 rupiah per
dollar previous estimate, and the inflation rate minus 0.5 percent,
from 17.4 percent at previous figure," spokesman of the Budget
Committee Simon Patrice Morin said.
</P>
<P>
The committee also agreed to revise the bill No.7/1999 on the
State Budget for fiscal year 1999/2000, under which targets of the
state income and its expenditure will experience significant
changes.
</P>
<P>
Under the draft of the revised-bill read out by Abdullah Zaeni,
a member of the committee , the state income for the fiscal year
1999/2000 is estimated to reach 245.325 trillion rupiah (32.911
billion U.S. dollars) while its expenditure is targeted to reach
245.191 trillion rupiah (32.893 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
"So the budget is expected to experience surplus mounting to
133.396 billion rupiah (17.895 million U.S. dollars)," Zaeni added.
</P>
<P>
The revised-bill of the country's 1999/2000 State Budget is
expected to be passed by the House in a plenary session next week
before validated by President Abdurrahman Wahid and takes effect.
</P>
</TEXT>
