<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Filipino Drivers Meted Death for Drug  Trafficking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Three Filipino drivers were meted
death sentence Thursday by a regional court here in Metro Manila
for drug trafficking, Philippine News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
The agency said Quezon City Regional Trial Court handed down
the decision against the three drivers who are aged 48, 39 and 21
respectively.
</P>
<P>
"The fact that all the accused were in one car and each had a
role in the consummation of the transaction proves that they had a
community of design," Quezon City Judge ose Mendoza said in his
nine-page decision.
</P>
<P>
The three were found guilty for violation of the Dangerous
Drugs Law for an unlawful sale of 634 grams of pseudoepherine
hydrochloride, a regulated drug.
</P>
<P>
The said drug is a raw material used for the preparation of
methamphetamine hydrochloride known as "shabu."
</P>
<P>
Under the Dangerous Drugs Law, the allowed therapeutic dose for
pseudoepherine is 15 to 120 milligram only and if it is far beyond
therapeutic requirements, the penalty is death sentence.
</P>
<P>
Court records showed that on September 22, 1998, the three
accused were nabbed by the Philippine National Police Narcotics
Group in a buy-bust operation for selling the 634 grams of
pseudoepherine hydrochloride. 
</P>
</TEXT>
