<HEADLINE> Indian, U.S. Sign Agreement Worth 1.4 Billion  Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Companies from the two countries signed 11 business agreements
which include four in the IT sector, three in environment, three
in power and one in tourism area.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the signing ceremony, visiting United States
Commerce Secretary William Delay said U.S. firms were very eager
to enter into agreements and do business with their Indian
counterparts.
</P>
<P>
"We are also willing to provide our experience and expertise to
the Indian companies," Delay said, adding the on-going visit of
President Bill Clinton provided a rich opportunity to promote
American commercial interest in India and the agreements signed
here today were a "win-win" situation for both sides.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Delay said implicitly that Washington would not lift
its economic sanctions against India imposed after its nuclear
tests in May 1998 before New Delhi signs the Comprehensive Test
Ban Treaty (CTBT).
</P>
<P>
However, Delay asked the Indian government to take steps to
increase import from the United States so as to reverse the trade
balance between the two countries which was heavily in New Delhi's
favor.
</P>
<P>
Official figures showed that India's exports to the U.S.
amounted to over nine billion U.S. dollars last year while imports
from the U.S. was only 3.7 billion dollars, with a balance of more
than 5.3 billion dollars in India's favor. 
</P>
