<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India to Allow 100 Pct Foreign Direct Investment in  Oil Refining Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
This decision was included in an inter-ministerial report
dubbed Hydrocarbon Vision 2025, which was submitted to Indian
Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee here on Thursday by Petroleum
Minister Ram Naik. The document will work as a policy spectrum for
the country's oil sector in the next 25 years.
</P>
<P>
The current government ceiling for FDI in the oil refining
sector was 49 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to Hydrocarbon Vision 2025, the government will also
merge standalone oil refineries in the public sector with the
petroleum marketing companies as it will be difficult for the
former to survive in the liberalized oil scenario from 2002
onwards, said Ram Naik.
</P>
<P>
He claimed that he would place the report before the Parliament
during its current session for necessary approval.
</P>
<P>
The Vision report, finalized by the ministerial group headed by
Finance Minister Yashwant Sinha, also recommended existing
subsidies be phased out over three to five years and an expert
group be set up to determine levels of tariffs and duties for
implementation in a phased manner, said Petroleum Secretary Dr.S
Narayan.
</P>
<P>
He said that the ministerial group recommended disinvestment in
a phased manner in oil PSUs in appropriate levels to realize
maximum shareholders value, but did not elaborate on the extent of
disinvestment.
</P>
<P>
It also suggested deregulation of overseas exploration and
production by Indian oil companies, he added. 
</P>
