<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Urged to Stop Dumping of U.S. Chicken Parts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 23 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Chamber of
Agriculture and Food Inc. (CAFI) urged the government Thursday to
stop the United States bid to dispose of its excess chicken parts
production by dumping them at low prices in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
CAFI said in a report that the government should only allow
whole chicken, instead of just broiler parts, to get in, so that
local products can become price competitive against imported ones.
</P>
<P>
The food chamber made the plea that measures should be taken
immediately, to avert the collapse of the 200-billion-peso (5-
billion-U.S. dollar) poultry industry.
</P>
<P>
Citing market intelligence reports, CAFI said American poultry
raisers had managed to dump some 31,899 metric tons of broiler
parts into the Philippines last year at an average price of 23
pesos (0.57 dollars) per kilo.
</P>
<P>
Last year's volume was 1,058 percent more than the 2,753 metric
tons dumped in 1998, CAFI said, adding that this rate of increase
even eclipsed the 895 percent growth rate of U.S. broiler parts
registered in Ukraine, the 388 percent in South Korea in the same
period.
</P>
<P>
The huge volume sold at extremely low price -- half the 50
pesos (1.25 dollars) per kilo domestic chicken production cost --
has adversely affected thousands of poultry growers so much that a
number of them are now contemplating of shutting down their
operations.
</P>
<P>
Other allied industries supplying requirements for poultry
raisers, including feed millers, veterinary products manufacturers,
transport workers, among others, are also feeling the crunch, CAFI
said.
</P>
<P>
"All these has got to stop. The government has to move fast.
Otherwise, hundreds of our member firms, not to mention
independent poultry raisers, will be forced to close down their
operation," CAFI added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000323.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Spends Huge Expenditure on Rail  Transportation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar government has spent a
huge expenditure on rail transportation, buying in various railway
facilities from at least three countries in an effort to better
its rail transportation performance.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest issue of the local Myanmar Times
journal, state-run Myanmar Railways (MR) recently purchased from
France diesel electric engines at a cost of 440 million francs (65
million U.S.dollars) and from Yugoslavia 402 new goods-wagons and
spare parts worth 28 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The MR is planning to put them to use to schedule more express
freight trains.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the MR has also imported from China 120 million
dollars worth of rails, locomotives, coaches, heavy machinery,
wireless transmission sets, signal equipment and spare parts which
are used to upgrade the country's rail transportation equipment
and services, the journal said.
</P>
<P>
According to a report of the country's financial, economic and
social conditions, the MR has been carrying out transport services
with 279 diesel locomotives, 41 steam locomotives, 679 carriages
and 3,339 wagons.
</P>
<P>
Express passenger and cargo services are being undertaken on
Yangon-Mandalay route and Mandalay-Myitkyina route, the two major
railroads linking the country's northern and southern parts, in
collaboration with private entrepreneurs on contractual basis and
short distance rail transport services are carried out by rail
buses.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that since 1988, Myanmar has built 1,
590.4 kilometers (km) of railroads and the distance has extended
to 6,058.4 km in 1999 from 4,468 km in 1988.
</P>
<P>
The country is currently engaged in extending its railroad
network still further. 
</P>
</TEXT>
