<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Urges Religious Followers to Observe Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 23 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian government
has appealed to followers of all religions to observe laws of the
country to avoid calamities like the one took place in Uganda
recently which killed more than 300 people.
</P>
<P>
The official Daily News Thursday quoted Permanent Secretary of
Tanzanian Ministry of Home Affairs Bernard Mchomvu as saying that
the right to worship is a constitutional one for all Tanzanians,
but the freedom has to be exercised within the parameters of the
law.
</P>
<P>
The government will not tolerate groups whose activities
threaten peace and tranquility or are antagonistic, said Mchomvu,
who is also Registrar of Societies, on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He warned that worshippers who pray naked or those who refuse
to take the sick to hospital, refuse to enroll their children to
school and those using abusive language, will not be tolerated.
</P>
<P>
According to Mchomvu, the number of registered and unregistered
 religious groups in Tanzania have been on the increase since
1998.
</P>
<P>
Between 1998 and this year, the ministry has received 32
applications from various religious sects seeking registration, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Out of them, 22 were registered and five were refused and seven
were deregisterd, he said.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the mushrooming of religious sects to external
influences from neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
Other reasons include the struggle for positions and the
scramble for money by religious leaders, while some just want to
be worshipped and seek to form their own groups, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
