<HEADLINE> 50 Killed in Nigerian Pipeline Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 23 (Xinhua) -- About 50 people were killed on
Wednesday by raging fire following an alleged vandalization at a
site of the pipeline of Nigerian National Petroleum Corporation
(NNPC) in the Abia state of eastern Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Charred bodies of the victims, burnt cans, bicycles and
motorcycles were seen at the scene, reminding people of the 1998
pipeline fire in Delta State, which killed about 1,000 people,
according to The Guardian, a leading Nigerian newspaper, on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Augustine Amgbala, a regional commander of the fire fighters,
was quoted as saying that his men had already exhausted their fire
fighting materials without extinguishing the fire.
</P>
<P>
He said that 28 suspected vandals have been arraigned in court
while 17 others are still being interrogated.
</P>
<P>
Items recovered from the suspects include oil tanker vehicles,
mini buses, pumping machines, motorcycles, bicycles and heavy
jerry cans filled with fuel.
</P>
<P>
He blamed the intermittent fuel scarcity in the southeastern
states on the "persistent vandalization of NNPC oil pipelines in
the zone."
</P>
<P>
He appealed to traditional rulers and community leaders to
co-operate with law enforcement agents by enlightening the people
on the dangers inherent in such acts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
