<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Launches Economic Blueprint </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian President Olusegun
Obasanjo has launched an economic blueprint with a target to
increase Gross Domestic Product growth rate from the present 2.4
percent to 10 percent by the year 2003, leading Nigerian newspaper
The Guardian reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo unfolded the macro-economic policies of his
administration Wednesday in the capital Abuja at the opening of
the meeting of the Federal Executive Council, the highest
policy-making body of the government, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
According to the document, which entitled: Nigerian Economic
Policy, 1999-2003, the Obasanjo's government would achieve by 2003
the targets, among others, the rise of the employment rate from 50
percent to 70 percent, the reduction of inflation rate to single
digit, the improvement of the electricity provision from 34
percent to 60 percent, the rise of literacy level from 57 percent
to 80 percent, and an easier access to telephone and water.
</P>
<P>
While elaborating the measures to achieve the macro-economic
goals, Obasanjo stressed that his government would take every
measure to improve the workings of the joint venture technical
committees, pledging to increase local involvement in those
sectors current dominated by foreign companies.
</P>
<P>
On macro-economic policies, Obasanjo said the government would
pursue stability in the price and exchange rate, ensure a healthy
balance of payments and allow interest rate to support the real
sector.
</P>
<P>
 He also give the highest priority to the agriculture both for
poverty reduction in the rural areas and improvement of the
economy.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo said his government, when inaugurated last May,
inherited an economy that reflected declining capacity utilization
in the real sector, poor performance of major infrastructure,
large budget deficit, rising level of unemployment and inflation.
</P>
<P>
He further stated that the guiding principle of his
government's economic thrusts would revolve around the people
because "the economy belongs to the people", stressing that the
economy "shall also be technology-driven, broad-based, humane,
open and internationally significant".
</P>
<P>
The objective of the policies was aimed to revive Nigeria's
ailing economy, significantly raise the standard of living of the
people, put Nigerians back to gainful work and create new
employment opportunities, said he. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
