<HEADLINE> Nigerian Government Rejects Calls for Sovereign Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's Obasanjo administration
Wednesday rejected a proposal for convening a sovereign national
conference to decide upon the validity of the sticky issues
including the introduction of Islamic Law Sharia
</P>
<P>
Information Minister Dapo Sarumi was quoted as saying by the
Daily Times, a major Nigerian newspaper published Thursday, after
a Federal Executive Council (FEC) meeting in Abuja.
</P>
<P>
He said: "the Federal Executive Council has no legislative
powers to summon a Sovereign National Conference, it is the
National Assembly that has the powers to do that. We took an oath
to defend the constitution and there is no place in the
constitution where we are empowered to summon a Sovereign National
Conference."
</P>
<P>
But he added it would be in the best interest of the nation to
remain a strong and united country.
</P>
<P>
The proposed conference had been quite a focus of Nigerian
media recently. Many people and organizations, especially in the
South of the country, had said such a forum was the only way to
find ways out of the country's multi-faceted problems.
</P>
<P>
But others said such a conference would go no where but to the
weakening of the federal government and further conflicts between
the states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
