<HEADLINE> Portuguese Premier Assures Austria's Participation in EU Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LISBON, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Portuguese Premier Antonio
Guterres assured Austria's full participation in the two-day
European Union summit beginning here Thursday but reaffirmed the
political sanctions imposed on Vienna by its 14 EU partners for
including the far-right party into the government.
</P>
<P>
Guterres, whose country is holding the rotating presidency of
the 15-nation bloc, said he planned to avoid debate on the issue
of Austria during the summit, though Austrian Prime Minister
Wolfgang Schuessel would try to use an official dinner to be
hosted by Portugal Thursday for the heads of state and government
of EU member states to appeal for a lifting of the freeze on
bilateral political relations.
</P>
<P>
Austria's 14 EU partners have been boycotting the country
politically since the swear-in of the Austrian coalition on
February 6. France and Belgium have time and again cold-shouldered
Austria on official occasions even though the European Commission,
the executive body of the 15-nation bloc, said that the bilateral
freeze would not affect the business of the EU institutions.
</P>
<P>
The inclusion of extreme rightist Joerg Haider's Freedom Party
into the Austrian coalition government stirred up a furor across
the EU member states, of which some are fearful of a possible rise
to state power of ultra-rightists in their own countries.
</P>
<P>
The Lisbon summit is not about Austria but about employment,
Guterres said before the summit kicked off to focus on issues of
employment, structural reforms, social cohesion, common European
security and defense policy, inter-governmental conference and the
Balkans.
</P>
<P>
The EU is scheduled to sign a trade pact with Mexico that is
expected to cut tariffs on 95 percent of two-way trade when coming
into effect on July 1 this year.
</P>
<P>
The EU-Mexico trade pact will give EU manufacturers and
producers almost as much access to the Mexican market as their
United States counterparts under the North American Free Trade
Agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
