<HEADLINE> Russia Refuses to Send Police to Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Russia on Thursday rejected a U.N.
request to send a special police force to Kosovo in protest of the
body's inability to check the negative trends in the Yugoslav
province.
</P>
<P>
"The entire responsibility for the unsatisfactory state of
security of the local population, for the failure to put an end to
ethnic clashes, and for the growing crime rate fully rests on the
current leadership of the U.N. mission in Kosovo," the Russian
Foreign Ministry said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
It voiced serious concern that "the negative trends in Kosovo
have gone too far; the security of the non-Albanian population is
steadily worsening; the activity of Kosovo terrorists and criminal
groups is increasing."
</P>
<P>
"The leaders of the U.N. mission in Kosovo and KFOR (the NATO-
led multinational peacekeeping force in Kosovo) do not fully
utilize the powers granted them by U.N. Security Council
resolution 1244 and the means at their disposal to stabilize the
situation in Kosovo," the Interfax news agency quoted the
statement as saying.
</P>
<P>
Moscow was surprised "about the stance of the U.N. Secretariat
and leadership of the mission in Kosovo on the speedy deployment
of an international police force in the area," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"On the one hand, they regularly point to the acute police
force insufficiency, on the other they have been obstructing for
several months and under various pretexts the arrival of Russian
Interior Ministry officials for operations with the mission police,
" the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"In this situation we are forced to rescind our agreement with
the U.N. request to send a Russian special police unit to Kosovo,"
the document said.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov
on Thursday reiterated Moscow's threat to withdraw its
peacekeepers from Kosovo if developments there "unfold according
to a worst-case scenario."
</P>
<P>
Russia has some 3,600 peacekeepers stationed in Kosovo as part
of the KFOR.
</P>
<P>
"If the situation worsens and the question of separating
Kosovo from Yugoslavia looks likely, Russia will not share the
responsibility for these developments with the countries that
encourage them," Ivanov said in an interview with the RTR
television station. 
</P>
</TEXT>
