<HEADLINE> Inner Mongolia Benefits From International Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, March 23 (Xinhua) -- North China's Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region last year was the recipient of five
international aid programs, worth a total of 14.6 million US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to the regional department of foreign trade and
economic cooperation, the aid programs are mainly concerned with
the region's medical care, disaster relief and special education
for the handicapped.
</P>
<P>
The five aid programs are sponsored by Japan, Germany and
Australia, local officials said.
</P>
<P>
Japan is implementing two aid programs in the region -- one
involves 1.06 million US dollars for secondary school education in
Hohhot, and the other involves 10.55 million US dollars for
improving medical conditions in the Xilin Gol League.
</P>
<P>
Germany's aid programs involve 2.9 million US dollars for road
construction in the Hulun Buir League and 52,000 US dollars for
the league's special education for handicapped children.
</P>
<P>
Australia has extended 53,000 US dollars to the Hinggan League
for disaster relief efforts.
</P>
<P>
Local officials said the aid programs have greatly improved the
living conditions of people in the underdeveloped parts of Inner
Mongolia, a Mongolian-dominated ethnic autonomous region on China'
s northern frontier.
</P>
<P>
They said the region has received a total of 41.3 million US
dollars in foreign aid since 1983, when it received its first
batch of international aid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
