<HEADLINE> Laid-off Women Offer Service to Lying-In Mothers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Yang Guiju was delighted to hear
that she had been accepted by a community-based company offering
services for lying-in women and their babies.
</P>
<P>
"I now have a new job and a solid foundation for my new life,"
said Yang, 37, who was laid off by a State-owned hotel in this
capital of northernmost China's Heilongjiang Province.
</P>
<P>
From today on, Yang and 39 other women who had also lost their
old jobs will work for the Lactation Company, the first of its
kind in the province to help women who have just given birth get
through the breast-feeding period.
</P>
<P>
Geng Danzhu, founder of the company, who is also the chief of a
local community service center, said that with the development of
the economy, people require more convenient and classified service
items. The main purpose of the Lactation Company is to provide
mothers and infants with services ranging from washing nappies to
preparing scientific diets, she said.
</P>
<P>
All the employees of the company are laid-off women workers who
want to work and have the experience of rearing children. "They
are patient," said Geng, "but their experience is still far from
enough."
</P>
<P>
According to Geng, her staff have undergone a professional
training program offered by doctors and nurses from the Harbin Red
Cross Hospital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
