<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Excavations to Protect 1,200-Year Old Tomb </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists are carrying
out excavations to protect an imperial tomb dating back to the
Tang Dynasty (618-907) in Pucheng County, in northwest China's
Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
The archeologists said it is the tomb of Li Xian, elder brother
of Emperor Li Longji.
</P>
<P>
The tomb is 80 meters wide and 1,000 meters long, while the
burial chamber is about 15 meters high and 30 meters in diameter.
</P>
<P>
There used to be a host of stone inscriptions and sculptures in
the shapes of humans and animals standing in front of the tomb,
but now only four of them are still there. They are symbolic
sacrificial objects.
</P>
<P>
Nearby are the tombs of imperial princes and princesses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
