<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Stresses Quality of Museum Exhibitions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 23 (Xinhua) -- China has chosen the annual ten-
top exhibitions among museums nationwide for 1999 in a bid to
better display the country's cultural heritage.
</P>
<P>
At an award ceremony for this year's best exhibitions today,
Zheng Xinmiao, deputy director of the State Administration of
Cultural Heritage, said, "Most of the museums are striving to
streamline their management and raise the quality of exhibitions."
</P>
<P>
The ancient tomb show in Mancheng in north Hebei Province, and
the nine others were chosen out of 45 entries.
</P>
<P>
While focusing on the exhibitions' artistic and academic value,
the awarded museums also have installed advanced equipment such as
ultraviolet glass shields and optical fibers for lighting in an
effort to protect the valuable cultural relics.
</P>
<P>
"The museums use their well-prepared exhibitions to attract
visitors and make profits," Zheng said.
</P>
<P>
The newly built exhibition hall of the Nanjing Museum combines
outer architectural style with exhibits, showing Nanjing's charm
as a well-known ancient Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Palace Museum specially schemed the packaging
art exhibition, introducing treasured packaged articles in the
imperial court of the Qing Dynasty (1644-1911).
</P>
<P>
Visitors could also view nomadic life of northern ethnic groups
from the ancient cliff pictures inscribed in the mountains of the
Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Tibet Museum and Sichuan Museum both arranged
unique shows featuring their local customs.
</P>
<P>
Zheng's administration hopes Chinese people will learn and
enjoy these museums.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics show that the country's relics protection
departments administer more than 1,300 museums housing over nine
million relics, and some 90 million people visit over 7,000
exhibitions last year.
</P>
<P>
The administration plans to increase the total number of
museums to 3,000 in 15 years, with at least one in every medium-
sized city.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
