<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Consumer Prices Down 5.1 Percent in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Consumer prices of Hong Kong in
overall terms registered a year-on-year decrease of 5.1 percent in
February 2000, slightly smaller than the 5.3 percent fall in
January, according to the Census of Statistics Department of Hong
Kong Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The smaller decline in the Composite Consumer Price Index (CPI)
in February was attributable partly to higher charges for package
tours around the Lunar New Year, and partly to firming up in the
retail prices of motor fuels, liquefied petroleum gas, jewelry and
certain consumer durables.
</P>
<P>
Clothing and footwear registered the largest year-on-year
decrease of 13.1 percent in the Composite CPI in February 2000,
followed by housing and consumer durables that declined by 10.4
percent and 6.3 percent in the Composite CPI, respectively.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, year-on-year increases were recorded for
fuel and light that were up by 3.8 percent in the Composite CPI.
</P>
<P>
A government secretariat spokesman noted that consumer prices
continued to decline, as retailers continued to offer substantial
price discounts on a wide range of consumer goods and services
amidst keen competition in the retail market.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
