<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Ranks Busiest Container Port </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong is the world's
busiest container port with its total throughput in 1999 reaching
more than 16.2 million TEUs (twenty-foot equivalent units), said
Hong Kong Secretary for Economic Services Stephen Ip today.
</P>
<P>
The figure represented a 11.2 percent increase on an annual
basis, he said, adding that the robust performance of the
container throughput was attributable to the acceleration of the
Asian economic recovery plus a significant upturn in transpacific
shipments in the second half of 1999.
</P>
<P>
On the outlook for the port of Hong Kong, Peter Thompson,
chairman of the Hong Kong Port and Maritime Board (PMB), said the
expanding South China cargo base would remain Hong Kong's main
cargo source.
</P>
<P>
"In addition, Hong Kong will have much to gain from the
spurring effect of China's imminent accession to the World Trade
Organization," Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
PMB forecast a seven percent growth in container throughput for
Hong Kong in 2000.
</P>
<P>
"Timely provision of port facilities is crucial to the success
of the port of Hong Kong," Chairman of PMB's Port Development
Committee Gerry Forsgate said.
</P>
<P>
"A key element of matching supply of port facilities with
demand is the accurate forecast of future port cargo demands. The
port cargo forecasts will provide crucial data for carrying out
realistic and accurate planning for future port facilities and the
provision of port-related infrastructure," Forsgate said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
