<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan's Military Leader to Visit Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's military ruler
General Pervez Musharraf will make a three-day working visit to
Malaysia beginning March 27.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Foreign Minister Syed Hamid Albar said Musharaff's
visit would allow Kuala Lumpur to get first-hand information on
the current situation in Pakistan since the military take over.
</P>
<P>
"We will know what action they will take to bring back Pakistan
to normalcy and to enable the country to once again become a
member of the Commonwealth," he told a news conference here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"He is coming as a leader of a country but our position on what
we think of a military junta replacing a civilian government
democratically elected does not change," Syed Hamid said
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's suspension from the Commonwealth was in line with
the organization's stance of not condoning military take-over of a
democratically elected government.
</P>
<P>
Syed Hamid said as a member of the Commonwealth Ministerial
Action Group, Malaysia is supposed to monitor the situation in
Pakistan and recommend to the Commonwealth Heads of Government
whether to reinstate Pakistan as a fully participating member of
the Commonwealth.
</P>
<P>
Syed Hamid said it is at his request that Musharraf will visit
Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
"This is a good opportunity to meet him and have discussions on
current state of Pakistan and on other bilateral issues," he said.
</P>
<P>
Musharraf toppled Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif on Oct. 12 last
year in a bloodless coup. He suspended Pakistan's constitution,
parliament and four provincial assemblies when he ousted Sharif.
</P>
<P>
However, Musharraf did not declare formal martial law, allowed
Sharif's handpicked Mohammad Rafiq Tarar to continue as president,
and did not ban political parties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
