<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Links Lifting Sanctions To Signing CTBT By  India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"India signing CTBT will not only remove sanctions but reduce
tension in the world," said visiting U.S. Commerce Secretary
William Daley after his hour-long meeting with Indian Finance
Minister Yashwant Sinha.
</P>
<P>
Asked when U.S. would lift the remaining sanctions imposed on
India following its nuclear tests in May 1998, Daley expressed his
hope that the sanctions become a thing of the past, saying even
the group of eight industrialized countries had asked India to
sign the CTBT.
</P>
<P>
India has hoped that, during the five-day visit by President
Bill Clinton, Washington would remove the sanctions which have
been gradually lifted.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with Sinha, Daley said, he emphasized the
need for India to further reduce tariffs to attract U.S.
investments into the South Asian country while Sinha expressed his
difficulty due to budgetary constraints.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a joint session of the Indian Parliament here on
Wednesday, Visiting U.S. President Bill Clinton promised to remove
all "existing impediments" to trade with India while urging India
further open up its economy.
</P>
<P>
Delay asked the Indian government to take steps to increase
import from his country so as to reverse the balance of trade
between the two countries which was heavily in New Delhi's favor.
</P>
<P>
Official figures showed that India's exports to the U.S.
amounted to over nine billion U.S. dollars last year while imports
from the U.S. was only 3.7 billion dollars, with a balance of more
than 5.3 billion dollars in India's favor.
</P>
<P>
Delay announced that the two countries would hold three cabinet
level dialogues focusing on finance and investment, cooperation on
trade and investment, and on commerce. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
