Clinton here on Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's visit to India, the first by a U.S. President in the
past 22 years, marks the beginning of a "whole new book" in Indo-U.
S. relations, said Ackerman.
</P>
<P>
"With the Cold War now over, there has been a change in south
Asian relationship and the president's visit lays to rest the
convention that U.S. imposes its will on India," he added.
</P>
<P>
Ackerman also revealed that Clinton would "be spending close to
three hours" in Pakistan in a "restricted area" during his brief
stopover in that country on his way home after the conclusion of
his five-day visit to India. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
