<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe News Agency Workers Return To Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 23 (Xinhua) -- The workers of Zimbabwe
Inter-Africa News Agency and Community Newspapers Group ended a
two-week long strike and returned to work on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The workers, who had been pressing for 80 percent salary
increase and 200 percent allowance increment, suspended their
strike after a meeting with President of Zimbabwe Union of
Journalists Mathew Takaona Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"The meeting resolved to suspend the strike after carefully
noting the promise made by President Robert Mugabe that our
grievances will be met soon," said spokesman for the Workers'
Committee Sydney Bonzo in a statement.
</P>
<P>
According to Bonzo, Permanent Secretary for Information, Posts
and Telecommunications Ministry Willard Chiwewe has promised to
find 30 million Zimbabwean dollars (780,000 U.S. dollars) for the
national news agency and 10 million Zimbabwean dollars (260,000
U.S. dollars) for Community Newspapers Group.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwe Union of Journalists and the Workers' Committee
will hold further meetings with the Ministry of Information, Posts
and Telecommunications and other relevant authorities to speed up
the resolution of the problems, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
