<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwandan President Resigns Over Make-up of New Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Rwandan President Pasteur
Bizimungu, an ethnic hutu, had resigned as a result of
disagreement with colleagues in the ruling tutsi-dominated Rwanda
Patriotic Front (RPF) over the make-up of a new cabinet which was
announced on Sunday, political observers said.
</P>
<P>
The RPF formed a government of national reconciliation which
sought to embrace both ethnic groups after the genocide of
hundreds of thousands of minority tutsis by hutu extremists in
1994.
</P>
<P>
But several senior officials belonging to hutu, including
Pierre Celestin Rwigema, have quit their positions since the new
government was formed.
</P>
<P>
Rwigema resigned last month as prime minister after a
parliamentary probe accused him of corruption.
</P>
<P>
It is said that most of the power in Rwanda now rests with Vice
 President Paul Kagame, a tutsi who is also chairman of the RPF.
 Rumors have been rife in Kigali for months about strained
relations between Kagame and Bizimungu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
