<DOCNO> XIE20000323.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Yet Decide to Quit COMESA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By Pang Yong
</P>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Despite of its plan to pull
out of the Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA),
the Tanzanian government has not decided to quit the regional
economic block, Tanzanian media reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking Wednesday at the Lusaka International Airport on his
way home from a visit to Namibia, Tanzanian President Benjamin
Mkapa stressed that the issue his country faces now is not whether
it should pull out of COMESA or not, but how many regional groups
it should belong to at one time.
</P>
<P>
"We have stakes in SADC (Southern African Development
Community), COMESA and the East African Community and yet there
are others who want us to join them," he said.
</P>
<P>
He insisted that Tanzania is yet to officially pull out of
COMESA, a regional community aimed at sharing the region's common
heritage and destiny to allow greater social and economic
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The decision will depend on recommendations by the
organization's ministers who will hold a consultative meeting next
month, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he said Tanzania's plan to pull out of COMESA does not
mean it lacks interest in pursuing economic integration.
</P>
<P>
On the re-launched East African Community, Mkapa explained that
it is aimed at strengthening economic and commercial relations of
the member states and therefore poses no threat to other regional
institutions.
</P>
<P>
Established in 1994, COMESA exists as an organization of free
and independent sovereign states that have agreed to cooperate in
developing their natural and human resources for the good of all
their people.
</P>
<P>
With a membership of 21 states and a population of 385 million,
it forms a major integrated trading block.
</P>
<P>
Many COMESA member states are also members of one or more
regional groupings such as the East African Co-operation, the
Southern African Development Community, Southern African Customs
Union, Intergovernmental Authority on Development, and Indian
Ocean Commission.
</P>
<P>
Some member States are concerned that their dual or even
multiple membership in these organizations will make it difficult
for them to implement agreed programs, including making membership
contributions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000323.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DPRK Declares Navigation Order Around Islands Under U.S. Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, March 23 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK) Thursday declared the order of navigation
to and from the five islands under U.S. control.
</P>
<P>
The communique said that if U.S. warships and civilian ships go
beyond the designated zones and waterways, it will be regarded as
"an outright intrusion into the territorial waters of our side and
waters and airspace under our military control," the Korean
Central News Agency (KCNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
In that case ,the communique said, the DPRK armed forces will
retaliate without warning.
</P>
<P>
After the West Sea conflict on June 15, 1999, the DPRK
negotiated the demarcation line on the West Sea with the United
States several times, but failed to reach an agreement.
</P>
<P>
The communique said: "We have made every possible effort to
settle through negotiations issues that may be raised between our
side and the U.S. forces side, among them an issue of navigating
to and from islands under the U.S. forces side's control under the
Korean Armistice Agreement."
</P>
<P>
"Now that the U.S. forces side finally refused to discuss the
issues, our side cannot wait any longer for its response to our
offer for a technical discussion. Therefore, the KPA Navy Command
was authorized to confirm and declare 'order of navigating to and
from five islands' situated in the territorial waters north of the
extension of the military demarcation line at the West Sea of
Korea," it said.
</P>
<P>
The waters around Paekryong, Taechong and Sochong islands shall
be designated as the first zone, the waters around Yonphyong
island the second zone and the waters around U island the third
zone, the communique announced.
</P>
<P>
U.S. warships and civilian ships, which are considered not
hostile, shall be allowed navigate in the first, second and third
zones through the corresponding waterways.
</P>
<P>
Planes are not allowed to fly over the islands "in principle"
except over the waterways in unavoidable cases, it said.
</P>
<P>
"If warships and civilian ships and planes of the U.S. forces
side go beyond the designated zones and waterways, it will be an
outright intrusion into the territorial waters of our side and
waters and airspace under our military control," the communique
said.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK threatened to retaliate without warning if the U.S.
side "dares to challenge."
</P>
<P>
A DPRK naval ship sank and three others were damaged in the
June 15 naval conflict between the DPRK and South Korean navies,
following which the DPRK established a West Sea demarcation line
but the U.S. side sticks to the "Northern Line." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000323.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
