<HEADLINE> Israel Urges Syria to Grasp "Last Opportunity" for Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Justice Minister Yossi
Beilin has urged Syria to make good use of the up-coming meeting
between the presidents of Syria and the United States to make
peace in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
"The meeting could constitute the last opportunity to reach
peace between Syria, Lebanon, and Israel," Beilin said in a
statement here Wednesday at the 56th session of the United Nations
Commission on Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
"Peace agreements in the Middle East in fact could be reached
by the end of year 2000.This is a rare opportunity which should
not be missed," he added.
</P>
<P>
Syrian President Hafez al-Assad and U.S. President Bill Clinton
are scheduled to hold talks on Middle East affairs here in Geneva
on March 26.
</P>
<P>
Hopes for the U.S.-Syria summit are high amid increasingly
strong signals that Syria and Israel may be close to a peace
accord.
</P>
<P>
While visiting the Middle East last month, Swiss Foreign
Minister Joseph Deiss offered to host a three-way summit among the
United States, Israel and Syria. 
</P>
