<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Delegation to Visit Baghdad for More Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 23 (Xinhua) -- A French business delegation will
start a seven-day visit to Baghdad on Saturday to promote trade
between France and Iraq, the Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, the delegation will meet Iraqi ministers and
other officials to discuss ways of strengthening bilateral economic
and trade cooperation, said INA.
</P>
<P>
The delegation groups representatives from 35 major French
companies, ranging from energy, petroleum, communications to
minerals, agriculture and banking sectors.
</P>
<P>
France, a traditional trading partner of Iraq, has been trying
to gain a slice of Iraq's lucrative market within the framework of
the U.N. oil-for-food program.
</P>
<P>
Under the oil-for-food deal launched in 1996, now in its seventh
phase, Iraq is allowed to sell a limited amount of oil every six
months and use part of the revenue, under the U.N. supervision, to
buy food, medicine and other humanitarian supplies for its 22
million people, who have been under crippling U.N. sanctions ever
since Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The French government has been urging French companies to
increase their investments in Iraq, and has sent a diplomat to run
an interests section in Baghdad for the first time since 1990,
besides the already-opened trade center in Baghdad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
