<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Company Fined for Oil Spill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 23 (Xinhua) -- An Australian company has been
fined more than 40,000 Australian dollars (26,400 U.S. dollars)
for allowing 2,000 liters of oil to spill into a storm water
channel, Environmental Protection Act (EPA) said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Oil and Fuel Salvaging Pty Ltd in Brisbane, the Queensland
state in east Australia, was fined 20,000 Australian dollars (13,
200 U.S. dollars) for unlawfully causing environmental harm on
June 29 last year, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
The company also had to pay 10,657 Australian dollars (7,033 U.
S. dollars) to cover the cost of the four-day clean-up.
</P>
<P>
Its directors Eleanor and John Mare were each fined 5,000
Australian dollars (3,300 U.S. dollars) for failing to comply with
the EPA.
</P>
<P>
EPA director Alan Feely said the total penalty sent a clear
message about the legal obligations of individuals and companies
regarding the environment.
</P>
<P>
Feely said the oil spill had the potential to damage mangrove
habitats in the Brisbane River.
</P>
<P>
He said it was the second time Oil and Fuel Salvaging had been
prosecuted for environmental breaches. 
</P>
</TEXT>
