<HEADLINE> Ugandan Cult Leaders Enlisted as Most Wanted People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan police have enlisted the
surviving leaders of the cult Movement for the Restoration of Ten
Commandments of God as most wanted people.
</P>
<P>
"We are still searching for them," police spokesman Asuman
Mugenyi told Xinhua in a telephone interview Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
"At present we have not confirmed Joseph Kibwetere and other
cult leaders have died in the inferno or are still on the run," he
said, adding that "there are conflicting reports on their fate."
</P>
<P>
"Whether they are alive or dead, they are wanted," the
spokesman said. " We have alerted relevant organs to be vigilant
and arrest the cult leaders once seeing them."
</P>
<P>
State Minister for Regional Cooperation Amama Mbabazi told the
New Vision daily on Wednesday that Kibwetere was still alive while
other reports here said that the cult leaders all died in the mass
suicide last Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to police sources, 530 people have been killed in the
mass suicide, the second biggest in the world, following the 1978
cult killing by People's Temple in Guyana in which more than 900
people died.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan authorities have issued a directive to disband the cult
and apprehend its leaders.
</P>
<P>
The cult, created in 1989 but registered in 1997, has been
working under the disguise of a non-governmental organization. It
has thousands of followers across the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
