<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police Oust Oscar Fans From Camp at Award Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, March 22 (Xinhua) -- Oscar fans were unhappy for
the termination of a decades-long tradition -- camping outside
Shrine Auditorium to get good seats to watch Sunday's Academy
Awards, because police ousted them away to make parking space for
elementary school students.
</P>
<P>
Some 30 campers, who had lined up to get a front-row seat on
the bleachers along the red carpet, were given just 45 minutes on
Tuesday to break camp and clear the sidewalks of an adjacent
street.
</P>
<P>
"We are just fans wanting to show our loyalty and be part of a
great event. For us to be treated so poorly, it doesn't seem right.
" said Lola Lopp, a mother of two from Riverside County.
</P>
<P>
A principal of a nearby elementary school complained that Oscar
fans occupied the parking space of the school. University of
Southern California students also have problems to get to their
apartments, because they must walk across the camp, police said.
</P>
<P>
A couple of fans, Susanne Wolf and Silvia Farag, said they flew
in from Frankfurt, Germany, to renew friendships they had struck
up with other fans attending the show during the past five or six
years.
</P>
<P>
Police, however, told the crowd who had gathered along
Jefferson Boulevard to pack up. Many signs reading "No standing,
no sitting, no furniture of any kind, no tents, sleeping bags or
blankets" are posted in the area.
</P>
<P>
Danielle Ferron, a 34-year-old masseuse from St. Malo, France,
said she saw a television report about the encampment, then bought
a ticket on the Internet and flew in Tuesday because it was "
something to try before getting too old."
</P>
<P>
Tina Hernandez, a 46-year-old secretary from Huntington Beach,
California, said she's been coming for 17 years and made so many
friends during the annual camp-out that she set up a Web site for
her group.
</P>
<P>
Her group pitched the first tent last Thursday. By Tuesday, 18
tents lined two sides of the street.
</P>
<P>
Diehard fans had arrived with coolers, tents, barbecues and
even generators to power TV sets. At stake are 200 first-come,
first-served stargazer seats in the fenced bleacher section
erected outside the cavernous Shrine Auditorium.
</P>
<P>
Showing sympathy with the fans, the Academy of Motion Picture
Arts and Sciences handed the ousted stargazers numbered vouchers
which give them priority spots in the bleachers, where they can
see their favorite celebrities entering the ceremony. 
</P>
</TEXT>
