<HEADLINE> Plane Crashes in Northeastern Spain, Causing Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, March 23 (Xinhua) -- A military C-212 cargo plane
crashed Wednesday night in Guadalajara, northeast of Spain,
causing fire in the forest, according to the report by the Civil
Guard of the country.
</P>
<P>
The fire have been put down but the whereabouts of the seven
crew members on board are unknown with the rescue work going on,
said the report.
</P>
<P>
The plane crashed three and half hours later after it took off
at 4 a.m. local time from a southern military base to Saragossa in
northeast Spain.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the Defense Ministry said that the reason for
the crash is still unknown so far, but as the plane has been burnt
out, the chance for the seven to survive is very rare.
</P>
<P>
This is the second air accident this month after two F-18
fighters crashed on March 13 near Saragossa, which killed one
pilot. 
</P>
