<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Continue Support for E. Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LISBON, March 23 (Xinhua) -- The European Union on Thursday
pledged continued support for East Timor's reconstruction and
transition toward a peaceful and democratic republic.
</P>
<P>
Portuguese Prime Minister Antonio Guterres, whose country is
holding the rotating presidency of the 15-nation union, said that
the EU was particularly concerned with the refugee problem with
still hundreds of thousands of them stranded outside East Timor.
</P>
<P>
About 130,000 East Timorese are still sheltering in refugee
camps in the Indonesian West Timor and United Nations officials
said that many are not returning home due to fears of a lack of
security and food.
</P>
<P>
"The EU would help lay down the foundation for the
reconstruction and contribute to peace of the region," said the
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Romano Prodi, president of the European Commission, the
executive body of the European Union, said that the union had
offered some 53.5 million euro (51.8 million U.S. dollars) to East
Timor and is expected to fish out another 20 million euro (19.4
million dollars) for between now and 2006 for the reconstruction
of East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Jose "Xanana" Gusmao, chairman of the National Council of
Timorese Resistance, expressed his gratitude to the EU
contribution and that of the international community and said that
without the outside assistance there would be no success in East
Timor.
</P>
<P>
The East Timorese independence leader said that East Timor
would be finally built into a democratic republic that can help
ensure peace and prosperity in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
