<DOCNO> XIE20000323.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Meteorology Day Marked in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 23 (Xinhua) -- China's close cooperation with
the international community has not only contributed to global
efforts in disaster reduction but has also benefited China itself
by improving its ability to forecast the weather and climate over
the past few decades, a top Chinese meteorological official said
here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a gathering marking today's World Meteorology Day,
and the 50th anniversary of the founding of the World
Meteorological Organization (WMO), Wen Kegang, director of the
China Meteorological Bureau, said that as a founding member of the
organization, China has been an active participant in global
cooperation in meteorology during the past five decades.
</P>
<P>
Wen's late predecessor Zou Jingmeng was twice elected chairman
of the organization during the past two decades, Wen said.
</P>
<P>
Zou was the first Chinese citizen elected head of a United
Nations organization.
</P>
<P>
During the past decades, China has been providing quality
weather and climate information obtained from its network of
weather observatories and stations across the country to other
parts of the world, the director said.
</P>
<P>
China also makes available to some countries weather and
climate information obtained through its own climate satellites.
</P>
<P>
Wen said China maintains close cooperation and exchanges in
meteorology with over 160 countries and regions, and has provided
meteorological instruments and equipment as assistance to about 50
countries in Asia, Africa, Latin America, and Europe during the
past decades.
</P>
<P>
China has also been a beneficiary of close cooperation with the
outside world, the director said.
</P>
<P>
Advanced equipment, including computers, and personnel training
outside China, has helped improve the capacity of Chinese
meteorologists, the director said.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 100 Chinese meteorologists have received training in the
United States in the past decades as part of bilateral cooperation
in science and technology, Wen said.
</P>
<P>
These people serve as not only the backbone of China's
meteorological efforts, but also as the leading force in China's
international cooperation with overseas colleagues, he added.
</P>
<P>
Among those also present at today's gathering were
representatives from the Chinese Foreign Ministry, the Ministry of
Water Conservancy, and leading Chinese meteorologists.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
