<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodian Police Capture Boat Hijacker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, March 23 (Xinhua) -- The Cambodian military police
have arrested one of the seven robbers who hijacked and robbed a
passenger boat on its way to Siem Reap Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
Chhaum Phai, 28, who was a military staff working in an
engineering unit, was captured in Phnom Penh at 10 p.m. Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The military police confiscated two AK-47s and lots of cash
from him, including 1,795 U.S. dollars, 319,400 Cambodian riel, 22,
000 Japanese yen, 400 pound sterling and 26,000 Vietnamese dong.
Also confiscated from the robber were five mobile phones, six
cameras, five watches and one recorder.
</P>
<P>
The robber now is under the police detention.
</P>
<P>
According to the military police, the rest of the robbers would
be arrested soon because the suspects have already been identified.
</P>
<P>
The hijacked boat, with 44 foreign and 46 local tourists, was
one of many boats that run daily between Phnom Penh and Siem Reap,
about 225 kilometers from the capital. A single trip takes some
five hours.
</P>
<P>
The hijacking occurred about an hour into the trip near Kompong
Luong town in Kompong Chhnang province.
</P>
<P>
The hijackers first tied up the passengers and cut the boat's
communications system, then robbed passengers' mobile phones, cash,
cameras and valuables.
</P>
<P>
After collecting their loot, the hijackers ordered the captain
to pull the boat near a riverbank before jumping overboard and
fled away.
</P>
<P>
It was learned that the foreigners on board were from about 10
countries, including the United States, Australia, France, Japan,
Italy and Germany. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
