<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Company Mergers Not to Affect Preferential Tax Policy: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 23 (Xinhua)-- China will not demand the return
of tax rebates on reinvestment when the foreign investor of an
enterprise with foreign capital transfers the reinvested project
to another company under the same group company, the State
Administration of Taxation announced today.
</P>
<P>
The administration made the announcement to address complaints
from some foreign investors that local tax bureaus have demanded
the return of tax rebates when the investor undergoes structural
changes.
</P>
<P>
Such enterprises include those that are wholly owned by foreign
investors and specially engaged in investment.
</P>
<P>
However, when the foreign investor company withdraws the
reinvestment by equity transfer or other means, it should return
the tax rebates it has received, the administration said.
</P>
<P>
To encourage foreign investment, China offers some tax rebates
for a five-year period to foreign investors in China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
