<HEADLINE> Australia Willing to Help China's Western Development (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Australia is willing to
participate in the development of China's vast western region in
the areas of rural development, poverty eradication, and resource
management, David Taylor Irvine, new Australian ambassador to
China, said here today.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark in his opening address delivered at a
symposium here hosted by the Australian Agency for International
Development (AusAID), a governmental department for overseas aid
projects in health, agriculture, rural development, infrastructure
construction, and other public areas.
</P>
<P>
With the participation of some 20 officials, experts, and
project leaders from both countries, the two-day symposium will
concentrate discussions on such topics as poverty elimination, the
improvement of rural health care, reform of the educational system,
and environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
Aid projects discussed at the symposium could promote poverty
relief efforts in western China, key to the country's strategy of
sustained development, Irvine said.
</P>
<P>
Irvine admitted that "poverty remains a major challenge for
China." Gaps in terms of development levels and income still exist
between China's inland and coastal areas, and between the incomes
of urban and rural residents.
</P>
<P>
However, he also highly praised China's poverty relief efforts,
noting that "some 200 million people have been lifted from poverty,
and substantial improvements have been recorded in China's human
development indicators" over the past two decades.
</P>
</TEXT>
