<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Further Opens to Foreign Investments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's powerful Higher Council for
Investment (HCI) has recommended lifting the ceiling on foreign
investments in key sectors to grant 100 percent ownership to non-
Jordanian investors in a bid to woo the much-needed foreign
investments.
</P>
<P>
The sectors to open to full foreign investments and ownership
include information technology, leasing companies, banking and
financing services, hospitals, hotels, communications, insurance,
environmental protection and catering services, the semi-official
Jordan Times newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The proposal, made during a HCI meeting chaired by Prime
Minister Abdel Rauf Rawabdeh earlier this week, is expected to be
approved next month, said the report.
</P>
<P>
If approved, foreign investors will be allowed to launch their
projects in the desert kingdom without the need to enter into
partnership with their local counterparts as required by current
laws and regulations.
</P>
<P>
However, some sectors are still expected to remain in the hands
of Jordanian investors or with a 50 percent ceiling of ownership by
foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
Financial clearing and settlement companies, distribution of
pharmaceutical products, real estate service and customs clearing
service will be confined to local investors.
</P>
<P>
Sectors which may absorb 50 percent of foreign investments are
retail trade, exports and imports, money exchange and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
The 50 percent ceiling was made at the request of the Amman
Chamber of Commerce, which believed that these sectors still need
stronger protection from the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
