<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton-Assad Summit Stirs High Hopes for Breakthrough </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 23 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton's
upcoming meeting with Syrian President Hafez al-Assad could bring a
breakthrough in Israeli-Syrian peace talks, despite ongoing
official attempts to play down the meeting, a senior Israeli
official said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton and Assad are to meet on Sunday in Geneva. Israeli
Deputy Foreign Minister Nawaf Massalha told the Jerusalem Post
newspaper Thursday that Clinton will bring to the meeting a
compromise proposal on the future borders between Israel and Syria,
which will be acceptable to both of them.
</P>
<P>
According to Massalha, a compromise has been worked out by the
Americans by which Israel would withdraw to the June 4, 1967, line,
while the Syrians were ready to be flexible regarding some small
modifications to the line.
</P>
<P>
Israel and Syria resumed their peace talks late last year, but
the talks have been stalled since January after two rounds. Syria
demanded that Israel promise to withdraw to the June 4 line and the
demarcation of borders be discussed first before tackling other
issues such as security, water and normalization of ties.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak met Wednesday twice with U.S.
ambassador to Israel Martin Indyk to discuss the Geneva meeting.
The two also discussed the visit to Israel next week of U.S.
Defense Secretary William Cohen, whose trip will deal in part with
American defense aid to Israel following a peace agreement reached
by Israel and Syria.
</P>
<P>
Barak also discussed the peace process on Wednesday in telephone
conversations with United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan and
French President Jacques Chirac.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Patrick Seal, the British journalist known to have
close ties with Assad and who was in Syria and Israel earlier this
month, told reporters in Vienna Wednesday that Clinton would bring
up a compromise solution on the border issue, stressing that Assad
would not come to the meeting if he did not intend on accepting the
compromise.
</P>
<P>
If there is a breakthrough in the Geneva talks, Barak will
probably be asked to go to Geneva for a meeting with Assad, other
sources here said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
