<HEADLINE> Philippines Makes Preparations for New School Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 23 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government is set
to deliver almost 5.9 million new textbooks and teacher's manuals
this May in time for the opening of school year 2000-2001, an
official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Education Undersecretary for External Affairs Victor Manhit
said a total of 5,891,703 textbooks will be delivered to the 26
beneficiary provinces of the Third Elementary Education Project (
TEEP), one of the major projects of the education department.
</P>
<P>
Likewise, a total of 170,711 teacher's manuals on the four
subject areas will be delivered with the textbooks.
</P>
<P>
Manhit also said 245 million pesos (6 million U.S. dollars) was
spent for the acquisition of textbooks and teacher's manuals which
was shouldered jointly by the government and the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, World Bank Country Director Vinay Bhargava reportedly
cited the Philippine educational system as one of the best in
Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
Bhargava said the Philippines is a good model of public
education in this part of the world, because of its accessibility
to the masses.
</P>
<P>
The literacy rate of the Philippines, which stands a 93.4
percent,is one of the highest in the world. 
</P>
