<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Tries to Lessen Dependence on Imported Oil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 23 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government will
continue to harness alternative sources of energy in helping
lessen the economy's dependence on imported oil and shield
consumers from the impact of price changes in the world market,
Philippine News Agency said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Energy Secretary Mario Tiaoqui was quoted as saying that the
present global situation, in which crude oil production is
controlled by a few, underscores the need for the country o tap
its indigenous and renewable energy sources.
</P>
<P>
"We are looking at other forms of energy so we would not be
totally dependent on crude oil," Tiaoqui said.
</P>
<P>
According to Tiaoqui, the government is making substantial
progress in tapping other sources of energy to lessen the
dependence of various sectors on imported crude.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, he noted, the country was 40 percent dependent on
imported oil for power generation, but this went down to 23
percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
For 2000, he said, the government hopes to bring this down
further to only 11 or 12 percent. Because o these efforts, he
added, the government can afford to temper oil price increases and
lessen their impact on the public.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the secretary said that as a result of efforts to
raise the country's energy self-reliance level, dependence on
imported oil has been reduced to roughly half of the national
energy requirements since 1999.
</P>
<P>
He said that compared with 1973 when the country was 92 percent
dependent on imported oil, the Philippines now buys oil to cover
only 47 percent of its energy requirements.
</P>
<P>
This significant reduction of oil dependence can be attributed
to the successful efforts by the government to harness indigenous
sources of energy, such as hydro and geothermal power and
agricultural wastes,Tiaoqui noted.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Estrada administration also continues to
develop renewable energy sources such as solar, wind and mini-
hydro power. 
</P>
</TEXT>
