<HEADLINE> Power Industry to Be Zambia's Leading Money Earner: COMESA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 23 (Xinhua) -- The Common Market for Eastern and
Southern Africa (COMESA) has said Zambia could make power
generation and distribution its leading money earner in the next
10 years, the Zambia Daily Mail newspaper reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The country has the biggest potential to generate and
distribute electricity to make the sector the number one earner
for the country in the next 10 years," the report quoted COMESA
Assistant Secretary General Sindiso Ngwenya as saying in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
The exports of electricity from Zambia to the region can
surpass the earnings from any sector including the mines, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Ngwenya, the Zambian government should "leave no
stone unturned to generate power for the regional market."
</P>
<P>
The realization of the prospect can be strengthened with the
exports of power to South Africa, which is expected to experience
a massive power shortage by the year 2008, he said.
</P>
<P>
South Africa has indicated that it will be experiencing a
massive power shortage by 2008. Its people are now looking at ways
in which they can meet that deficit. This is the opportunity for
Zambia to see what it can do to take advantage of the situation
and supply the electricity to South Africa, Ngwenya said.
</P>
<P>
He said Zambia should put special emphasis on power, noting
that realizing full export earnings from the sale of power does
not get affected by world trends for market demands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
