<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, March 23 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA -- Indonesian former president Soeharto is healthy
enough to face questioning for alleged corruption during his three-
decade rule, according to a report from an independent medical
examination team.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto was declared medically fit after undergoing two
examinations last week, the Jakarta Post Thursday quoted a source
close to the state-appointed medical team as saying. But the
source would not say whether questioning the 78-year-old former
ruler would be feasible since he has trouble in speaking. (
Indonesia-Former President)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KIEV -- Ukraine on Wednesday urged the European Bank for
Reconstruction and Development (EBRD) to resume loans to support
the country's construction of new nuclear stations.
</P>
<P>
After talks with visiting EBRD Vice President Charles Frank,
Ukrainian Prime Minister Viktor Yushchenko told a press conference
that the Ukrainian government has been "responsibly" meeting its
commitments under agreements on bilateral cooperation programs. He
promised that his government would shut down the Chernobyl nuclear
station in accordance with regulations in the memorandum signed in
1996 with the Group of Seven industrialized countries and the
Commission of the European Union. (Ukraine-EBRD-Loans)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Ethnic Albanian leaders in Kosovo do not want to
see the return of refugees of other ethnic groups, United Nations
High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) Sadako Ogata said here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Ogata told a news conference that over the past year ethnic
Albanian leaders have not only been against the return of non-
Albanian refugees, but have also sought to drive all remaining non-
Albanian residents out of the Yugoslav province, in serious
violation of the UNHCR principle providing for the return of all
refugees. She said the UNHCR mission in Kosovo will do its best to
persuade Serbs in Kosovo not to leave their homeland. (Yugoslavia-
Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. House of Representatives on Wednesday
approved a bill pressuring the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries (OPEC) to raise production and reaffirming President
Bill Clinton's authority to cut U.S. aid and arms sales to OPEC
members and nations that fix world oil prices.
</P>
<P>
The 382-to-38 vote in favor of the bill came just five days
before OPEC meets in Vienna to decide whether to boost production.
The legislation, offered by Benjamin Gilman, the New York
Republican who chairs the House International Relations Committee,
requires the president to report to Congress within 30 days on
which OPEC nations have fixed oil prices, and negotiate with other
countries to "reduce, suspend or terminate" military assistance
and arms exports to countries found to have "engaged in price
fixing." (US-Bill-Approval) 
</P>
</TEXT>
