<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Record Viewers To Watch Oscars Online </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, March 22 (Xinhua) -- This year's Oscars may not
only draw the biggest number of viewers on television -- but also
online, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to some 1 billion TV viewers around the world, the
analysts believe, more people than ever will watch the Oscars
online as tens of millions are expected to click their way into
the movie industry's most publicized drama.
</P>
<P>
Last year, more than two million viewers caught the annual
awards night on the Net, the analysts pointed out, adding that the
number is expected to increase ten-fold this year.
</P>
<P>
More than 30 Web sites will focus on the Oscars ceremony or
related events when the Academy Awards are handed out at the
Shrine Auditorium in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
Leading the cyber way is Oscar.com, a joint venture of the
Academy and Disney-owned GO.com and ABC.com. It promises to take
viewers backstage, showing the winners live as they talk to the
press -- it's the first time the Academy allowed this.
</P>
<P>
Brian Bowman, vice-president and general manager of ABC.com,
says the Web site is an enhancement to the telecast. "We can offer
things online you don't see on TV, but at the same time, if you
are watching two screens, your television and your PC or laptop,
it makes it a much more enriching experience," he said.
</P>
<P>
Other sites covering the event include Hollywood.com. It
promises to give visitors backstage passes, complete updates with
soundbites and chat rooms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
