<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Trade Representative Advocates China's Accession to WTO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, March 22 (Xinhua) -- The agreement between China
and the United States on China's accession to the World Trade
Organization (WTO) is mutually beneficial to both countries and
contributes to the long-term U.S.-China relations, U.S. Trade
Representative Charlene Barshelfsky said here Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
Specifically, she said, the agreement will create enormous
opportunities for American exports and export-related jobs, for
continued China's economic reform and for the global trading
system.
</P>
<P>
Addressing an audience of more than 100 people at a meeting
hosted by Town Hall Los Angeles, Barshelfsky said that China, one
of the largest countries in the world, should not be isolated from
world trade.
</P>
<P>
Explaining the importance of China's accession to the WTO and
urging U.S. Congress to approve the Permanent Normal Trade
Relations (PNTR) status for China, Barshelfsky said that she
expects the United States to double its exports to China in the
following years under the agreement.
</P>
<P>
The historic bilateral market access agreement between China
and the United States, which sets forth the terms for China's
accession to the WTO, was reached last November after seven years
of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Barshelfsky said that she expects U.S. congress to approve the
PNTR status for China before the end of May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
