<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Calls for Int'l Efforts to Resolve Kashmir Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan President Rafiq Tarar
Thursday urged the international community to facilitate the
solution of the long-standing Kashmir issue.
</P>
<P>
Addressing at the Pakistan Day parade here, Tarar expressed the
hope that the world would not act as a "silent spectator" over the
dispute and "would try to realize the promises made to Kashmiri
people through the United Nations by the entire world community."
</P>
<P>
Kashmir is a disputed area on the upper subcontinent of which
Pakistan controls some one third and India holds the rest and over
which the two South Asian neighbors have fought two wars during
the past half century.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations passed a resolution in 1949 calling for the
plebiscite of Kashmiris to determine the belongingness of the area.
However, the resolution has never been implemented.
</P>
<P>
Reiterating Islamabad's unequivocal support for Kashmiris'
freedom movement, Tarar said his country wants a peaceful
settlement of the Kashmir issue as it "is an issue linked to the
survival of Pakistan."
</P>
<P>
Pakistan believed in peace and did not intend to engage in any
arms race, the president said, adding "but we are fully capable to
give telling responses to any aggression."
</P>
<P>
He referred to the Kargil conflict last summer, which went so
close to a fourth Pakistan-India war, as "a glittering example"of
such "telling responses."
</P>
<P>
Pakistan on Thursday is celebrating the 60th anniversary of the
Lahore Resolution that led to the birth of the Muslim country on
the subcontinent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000323.0265 </DOCNO>
