<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyanide Dissolved into PNG Local Water System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Up to 150 kilograms of deadly
cyanide has dissolved into a local water system in Papua New
Guinea (PNG) after a crate of the chemical was accidentally
dropped from a helicopter, an Australian mining company admitted
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The accident happened on Tuesday as the company, Dome Resources,
was transporting two one-ton boxes of the pellets to the Tolukuma
gold mine, where the chemical is used for processing gold ore.
</P>
<P>
Twenty kilometers short of the mine, one package broke away
from a sling underneath the helicopter, plunged into the jungle
area, about 85 kilometers north of Port Moresby, and smashed apart
on impact.
</P>
<P>
Dome Managing Director Silver said some of the cyanide would
have dissolved in the rain and washed into local streams but there
would be no major environmental impact.
</P>
<P>
"Something like 100 to 150 kilos would probably have dissolved,
" he said.
</P>
<P>
"Fortunately the area in which it has landed is very sparsely
populated and it's an area which doesn't have a lot of streams
flowing in it," he added.
</P>
<P>
Dome Resources said clean-up teams had recovered up to 70
percent of the one ton of the cyanide dropped into jungle.
</P>
<P>
Silver said topsoil was being stripped from the immediate area
and taken to the mine for treatment.
</P>
<P>
Other chemicals are being used to neutralise the cyanide, he
said.
</P>
<P>
PNG disaster authorities have warned local villagers not to
drink from nearby rivers.
</P>
<P>
Even small quantities of cyanide can be lethal if ingested.
</P>
<P>
Greenpeace compared the incident with the recent cyanide
poisoning of rivers in central Europe by a Romanian mine half-
owned by Australia's Esmeralda Exploration.
</P>
<P>
Greenpeace said the PNG accident was another blow to the image
of Australian mining.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000323.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stricter Laws Called for after PNG Cyanide Accident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 23 (Xinhua) -- A cyanide accident in Papua New
Guinea (PNG) highlighted the need for stronger laws governing
Australian companies operating overseas, the Australian Democrats
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Democrats environment spokesman Andrew Bartlett said a
voluntary code of environmental management is inadequate.
</P>
<P>
"This highlights the need for environmental protection laws to
have some sort of binding effect on Australian companies operating
overseas," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is not just Australia's reputation but the reputation of
the Australian companies operating overseas," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Australian mining company Dome Resources admitted that up to
150 kilograms of deadly cyanide may have dissolved into a local
water system in PNG after a ton of the chemical was accidentally
dropped from a helicopter on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Dome Managing Director Michael Silver assured the community
that the company was using chemicals to try to neutralize the
cyanide, but said he could not guarantee nobody would be adversely
affected.
</P>
<P>
Bartlett said holding out hope is not good enough, with people
and the environment under threat of contamination.
</P>
<P>
"I think we need to do a lot more than just hope that people
will not be put in danger," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We need to have legal enforceable requirements that every step
is taken to prevent people being put in danger and the environment
placed in danger," he added.
</P>
<P>
Bartlett has joined the Australian Greens Senator Bob Brown in
urging the government to tighten the voluntary code after an
Australian mining company was linked to a cyanide spill in Romania
in February. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000323.0268 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU, Nigeria Sign Development Funding Pacts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, March 23 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) and Nigeria
signed here on Wednesday three development funding agreements
worth some 32.8 million euros (one euro is about one U.S. dollar),
signaling the restoration of such assistance after the country
resumed civil rule last year.
</P>
<P>
These agreements were signed by Philip Asiodu, chief economic
adviser to President Olusegun Obasanjo and Poul Nieson, EU
commissioner for Development Cooperation and Humanitarian Aid.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreements, about 21 million of the sum will go into
"micro- projects programs" for Nigeria's troubled Niger delta
region and be used for much needed water supply, inter-village
transport, health and income generation projects.
</P>
<P>
Ten million euros will be allocated to help the economic
management capacity project in a bid to strengthen key government
institutions such as the central bank, the Finance Ministry, the
Federal Office of Statistics and the National Planing Commission.
</P>
<P>
The third area the aid goes is programming study which will
enable Nigeria and the EU to establish guidelines for mid-term and
long-term cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Signing the agreements during the ongoing 30th session of the
African, Caribbean and Pacific Associates-EU Joint Parliamentary
Assembly, Nieson described the signature as "tangible proof of the
EU's commitment to its future relations with the Africa's most
populous country."
</P>
<P>
Funding of major EU projects in Nigeria was suspended five
years ago to protest alleged human rights abuses by the military
regime of Sani Abacha, who died in June 1998.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions were lifted in June 1999 after the country
embraced democracy in the previous month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
