<DOCNO> XIE20000323.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Urged to Sign SACU Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 23 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government has been
urged to resolve outstanding issues over the Southern African
Customs Union (SACU) and to sign the agreement as quick as
possible, the Times of Zambia newspaper reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Farmers had for two years been waiting for the signing of the
SACU agreement to enable them to fulfil their export quotas, Ajay
Vashee, president of Zambia National Farmers Union, was quoted by
the paper as saying on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The delay has made the farmers lose an opportunity to increase
the quotas given under the South Africa veterinary protocol, he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said the government's delay to finalize the SACU agreement
is killing Zambia's export potential in beef, oil crops and
fruits.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Zambia is expected to export 10,000 tons of soya
beans, 1,500 tons of beef, 5,000 tons each of groundnut and soya
bean cakes and two million litres of orange juice.
</P>
<P>
Other quotas include 1,000 tons each of dried beans, soya bean
oil and cotton cake, 500 tons of sunflower cake, 210 tons of green
peas and 135 tons of baby vegetables.
</P>
<P>
According to Vashee, large scale farmers have the capacity to
fulfil these quotas and if the agreement had been signed they
would have created room for small and medium scale producers to
satisfy local demand.
</P>
<P>
SACU agreement now has a membership of five countries,
including Namibia, South Africa, Swaziland, Botswana and Lesotho.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
