<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sand Sweeps Chinese Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 23 (Xinhua) -- The five-six degrees of the
disgusting Boreas last night has brought sand to the Chinese
capital for the third time this month.
</P>
<P>
Buildings, autos, and roads were covered with a thin layer of
sand after a night of northerly winds. Meteorologists said that
higher temperature in the beginning of March, scant precipitation,
and loosing earth, are the main reasons for the sand storms.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, cold air from Mongolia, together with sand
storms in north China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region worsened
the condition, said the local meteorological station.
</P>
<P>
Local officials said that they will put more efforts into
dealing with the pollution, and as part of the efforts they have
required all construction companies to take feasible measures to
lessen blowing dust while demolishing old buildings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
