<HEADLINE> Exhibition Against Pseudoscience Opens in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 23 (Xinhua) -- A large exhibition advocating
science and criticizing pseudoscience is being held in Beijing
from March 21 to 28.
</P>
<P>
More than 400 pictures exposing the truth of pseudoscience and
superstitious activities are on display, and the Falun Gong cult
and the harm it has done to society are also seriously criticized
at the exhibit.
</P>
<P>
China has launched a new campaign against superstition, which
has been surging in the country recently and disturbing social
stability and development.
</P>
<P>
A survey conducted by the China Association for Science and
Technology (CAST) shows that 35.5 percent of all Chinese citizens
believe in fortune-telling and divination, a figure nearly seven
percentage points higher than the percentage in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Yutai, vice president of CAST, said during the opening
ceremony of the exhibit that China should increase people's
scientific awareness and spread scientific knowledge and the
scientific spirit, method, and attitude.  
</P>
</TEXT>
