<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, March 23 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA -- The continual rise in interest rates in the United
States will affect the recovery of Brazil's economy, said
economists and analysts of this country on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Federal Reserve increased Tuesday the overnight lending
rate by a quarter point, and the majority of specialists think
necessary one or two further adjusting until the end of this year.
Since June 1999, five increases in U.S. interest rates have been
registered. (Brazil-US-Interest Rate)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MAPUTO -- Mozambique, facing a new flood surge after nearly
two months of ruinous rains, Wednesday appealed to the world for a
further 100 million U.S. dollars for flood relief and
rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
The southern African country had asked for 65.5 million dollars
on February 24 and received a total of 58.7 million dollars since
then. (Mozambique-Aid-Appeal)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. Senate unanimously passed legislation 100-0
Wednesday to repeal the Social Security earnings ceiling.
</P>
<P>
Both parties voted to quit taking Social Security benefits away
from people who continue to work through their late '60s to woo
the older voters in the election year. (US-Senate-Earning Ceiling)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazil, a traditional crude importer, will be self-
sufficient in oil until the year 2005, said President of the state
oil company Petrobrs Henri Philipe Reichstul on Wednesday in Sao
Paulo.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the South American country produces 1.3 million
barrels per day (bpd) of oil, meeting only 70 percent of the
countries necessity. (Brazil-Oil)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ROME -- The International Monetary Fund forecast Wednesday that
the Italian economy would grow by more than 2.5 percent this year
but warned that the inflation rate would be higher than expected.
</P>
<P>
According to Italian news agency Ansa, the head of the IMF team
of inspectors Maxwell Watson said that growth in Italy could be as
high as 2.75 percent in 2000. (Italy-IMF)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- A cut in tariffs by the European Union (EU) on
agricultural imports from Brazil would favor an expansion of
bilateral trade, Brazil's Agriculture Minister Pratini de Moraes
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with visiting EU commissioner on Foreign Trade,
Pascal Lamy, De Moraes presented his government's programs to
promote exports of chickens, pork, beef, fruits, fish and coffee
to the EU.  (Brazil-EU-Tariff ) 
</P>
