<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Trade Surplus Rises 26.8 Percent in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Japan's merchandise trade surplus
totaled 1,181 billion yen (11 billion U.S. dollars) in February,
up 26.8 percent from a year earlier for the first rise in 11
months, the Finance Ministry said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The surplus increase was attributed to a steep rise in exports
which outweighed a gain in imports.
</P>
<P>
Exports jumped 15.0 percent to 4,134 billion yen (38.6 billion
dollars), while imports surged 10.9 percent to 2,953 billion yen (
27.6 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Japan's exports rapidly grew on a robust demand for Japanese
information and telecommunications equipment. Shipments of
semiconductors and related electronic parts, optical equipment for
scientific use and telecom equipment rose 30.8 percent, 28.1
percent and 53.1 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Japan's politically sensitive trade surplus with the United
States climbed 66.0 percent to 687.3 billion yen (6.4 billion
dollars), the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
With Asian neighbors, Japan's merchandise trade surplus soared
94.4 percent to 403.7 billion yen (3.8 billion dollars), with
exports surging 32.0 percent and imports growing by 19 percent.
</P>
<P>
Japan's trade surplus with the 15-member European Union (EU)
went up 5.8 percent to 369.4 billion yen (3.5 billion dollars) for
the first upsurge in 14 months.
</P>
<P>
Japan's merchandise trade balance is measured on the basis of
goods clearing customs and is reported before adjustments for
seasonal variations.
</P>
<P>
The yen averaged 107.11 to the dollar in February, up 6.6
percent from the previous year's level. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000323.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pipeline Size of Foreign Aid Rises Sharply in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 23 (Xinhua) -- A sharp gap between commitment and
disbursement of aid money has inflated the size of foreign aid in
pipeline over the years, and the situation is unlikely to change
because of the donors' changed aid policies, said a government
document presented Thursday in a special cabinet meeting for
endorsement.
</P>
<P>
The document, prepared for placing in the next Paris
Development Forum meeting scheduled on April 13-14, estimated the
size of the aid money in the pipeline at 6.327 billion U.S.
dollars at the end of current fiscal year (1999-2000).
</P>
<P>
The amount went up from 4.963 billion dollars in 1998-1999 and
4.693 billion dollars in 1997-1998, showing that the pipeline size
of the foreign aid was increasing faster than ever before.
</P>
<P>
The document attributed the sharp increase of the pipeline
money to the slow disbursement of aid against the annual
commitments.
</P>
<P>
"As witnessed from the foreign aid statistics, disbursement is
not increasing significantly despite a rise in commitments," said
the document, stressing the need for efficient implementation of
projects.
</P>
<P>
The document said the development partners of Bangladesh have
changed their attitudes and strategies in making fresh aid
commitments as they are willing to see that aid is being used for
socio-economic changes and strengthening the base of economic
management.
</P>
<P>
They also laid importance on poverty alleviation, eradication
of corruption, establishment of transparency and accountability in
governance, liberalization of economy and consolidation of
democracy.
</P>
<P>
While going through the recent development in the economy, the
document projected a 5.5 percent growth in the gross domestic
products in the current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The document also projected a sharp increase in fiscal deficit
for the current fiscal year, the amount of which is estimated at
120.27 billion taka (2.31 billion dollars), showing a significant
jump from 100.64 billion taka (1.93 billion dollars) in the fiscal
deficit during the 1998-1999 fiscal year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
