<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 23 (Xinhua) -- The much-cherished comprehensive
trade agreement granting duty-free access of Bangladeshi products
to the European Union market is likely to be signed in May,
Commerce Minister Abdul Jalil was quoted Thursday by The New
Nation as saying.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the trade agreement was first scheduled on March
20 but deferred to April 10 due to U.S. President Clinton's visit
to Dhaka on the day. Now it has been deferred again to sometime in
May.
</P>
<P>
The commerce minister said following the European Union, other
important countries like Japan are also likely to permit duty-free
access of Bangladeshi exports.
</P>
<P>
Regarding Bangladesh's approach to get duty-free access to the
U.S.market, Jalil said they had got positive response from the U.S.
side during Clinton's visit on March 20.
</P>
<P>
He said the Bangladesh mission in the United States would
closely monitor and follow up the issue that has been raised
during Clinton's visit.
</P>
<P>
