COLOMBO, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka is to build 7,500
houses under a large-scale housing program to cater to the
increasing demand for housing, the Board of Investment (BOI) said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The BOI said in a statement that under the program, 25 new
projects will be launched in urban areas with each project
consisting of 300 houses to be completed in three years.
</P>
<P>
A large proportion of the houses will be allocated for low and
middle income families, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
According to the Presidential Task Force on Housing and Urban
Development, Sri Lanka has been short of about 170,000 urban
houses by the end of 1996.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that by the year 2005 over 500,000 houses will
be needed, of which more than half will be in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
The BOI will soon call for proposals from private sector
investors to build new houses under the housing program.
</P>
<P>
Under the program the government will provide the land on
concessional terms and will provide common infrastructure upto the
periphery of the housing project sites, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
It said three large projects providing upto 4,000 houses were
under construction by private sector developers who have been
given similar concessions in the government's effort to expand
housing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
