<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. House Approves Bill Pressuring OPEC to Increase Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 22 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. House of
Representatives on Wednesday approved a bill pressuring the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) to raise
production and reaffirming President Bill Clinton's authority to
cut U.S. aid and arms sales to OPEC members and nations that fix
world oil prices.
</P>
<P>
The 382-to-38 vote in favor of the bill came just five days
before OPEC meets in Vienna to decide whether to boost production.
</P>
<P>
The legislation, offered by Benjamin Gilman, the New York
Republican who chairs the House International Relations Committee,
requires the president to report to Congress within 30 days on
which OPEC nations have fixed oil prices, and negotiate with other
countries to "reduce, suspend or terminate" military assistance
and arms exports to countries found to have "engaged in price
fixing."
</P>
<P>
This "spotlights OPEC's price-fixing activities" and "sends a
clear message to the administration and to the oil producing
nations that oil price fixing is harmful to the American consumer,
" said Gilman.
</P>
<P>
The measure prompted a heated partisan debate over the Clinton
administration's energy policies and whether the bill, in fact,
would have any substantive impact on current, or even future oil
prices.
</P>
<P>
Democratic opponents to the measure said the legislation had no
teeth and that if the Republican-controlled Congress really wanted
to reduce U.S. dependence on OPEC oil, it should pass tax credits
and funding for research that develop alternative energy sources.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Energy Secretary Bill Richardson said the legislation
would interfere with his diplomatic efforts with OPEC oil
ministers, and therefore the administration would oppose the bill.
Similar legislation is also pending in the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
OPEC must boost crude oil output by about 2 million barrels per
day to return world stocks and prices to normal levels, according
to the U.S. Energy Information Administration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
