<HEADLINE> East China City Residents Donate 14 Tons of Blood in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Nearly 100,000 people in Nanjing,
capital city of east China's Jiangsu Province, donated a total of
14 tons of blood last year, an official with a local blood
donation center said today.
</P>
<P>
Wang Ningwu, director of the Blood Donation Office at Nanjing
Red Cross Blood Center, said the donated blood is enough to meet
the city's clinical use.
</P>
<P>
With a population of over two million, Nanjing started a blood
donation campaign in 1986, one of the earliest among all Chinese
cities, Wang added.
</P>
<P>
Since China's Blood Donation Law took effect in 1998, more and
more Nanjing people have joined the campaign for blood donation
with leaders at all levels taking the lead, he said.
</P>
<P>
Six vans for blood donations are shuttling around the city to
collect blood from volunteers and the campaign slogan "donating
blood is love, courage and sacrifice" has touched many hearts.
</P>
<P>
These vans collect more than half of the city's donated blood,
according to sources with the blood center.
</P>
<P>
To further promote the campaign, a special building for blood
donation was recently set up along the street of downtown Nanjing,
which is believed to be the first of its kind in the country.
</P>
<P>
The special building will facilitate people to donate blood
with its complete equipment and efficient service, the sources
added.
</P>
<P>
According to China's Blood Donation Law, a blood donator or his
or her relatives can receive free blood donations three times the
amount he or she gives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
