<HEADLINE> Medical Program Helps People In North China Province Regain Eye Sight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, March 23 (Xinhua) -- More than 16,000 cataract
patients in north China's Shanxi Province have regained their eye
sight in the past two years thanks to the efforts of members of a
state-sponsored medical team who performed surgery free of charge.
</P>
<P>
The team was part of a "Sight First China Action" program that
was launched in 1997 by the Ministry of Health, the Chinese
Disabled Persons Federation, and Lions Club International.
</P>
<P>
The program is aimed to help 1.75 million Chinese people regain
eye sight and train 11,000 ophthalmologists for rural hospitals
across the country in the 1997-2000 period.
</P>
<P>
They began working in the province in 1997 and have performed a
total of 17,600 operations on people suffering from cataracts in
poverty-stricken counties.
</P>
<P>
The team members will continue to perform such operations in a
period of five years for 46,000 patients in the province's remote
rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Now the province has 152,000 people suffering from eye sight
problems.  
</P>
</TEXT>
