<HEADLINE> Indonesian Former President Soeharto Fit to Face Questioning: Source </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian former president
Soeharto is healthy enough to face questioning for alleged
corruption during his three-decade rule, according to a report
from an independent medical examination team.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto was declared medically fit after undergoing two
examinations last week, the Jakarta Post Thursday quoted a source
close to the state-appointed medical team as saying.
</P>
<P>
But the source would not say whether questioning the 78-year-
old former ruler would be feasible since he has trouble in
speaking.
</P>
<P>
Asked to confirm the report, Attorney General Marzuki Darusman
said that it was possible to assume Soeharto was fit to face
questioning.
</P>
<P>
"I have read the report and it is possible to conclude that
from the report of the RSCM (Cipto Mangunkusumo Hospital) medical
team it is possible to hold further questioning on Pak Harto (
Soeharto)," Marzuki said.
</P>
<P>
According to the Jakarta Post, the Attorney General's Office
received the report from the state-appointed doctors on Wednesday.
Earlier the six-member medical team was seen visiting President
Abdurrahman Wahid at presidential office.
</P>
<P>
Director of Corruption Affairs in the Attorney General's Office
Chaerul Umam acknowledged that the report had been received but
refused to divulge whether it had given a green light for
prosecutors to start questioning Soeharto.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto was examined by six doctors from RSCM twice last week
to determine whether he is fit to face questioning. The doctors
included an internist, a cardiologist, a neurologist and a
psychologist.
</P>
<P>
The decision to conduct an independent medical examination on
Soeharto was taken after the former president's lawyers insisted
that their client was medically unfit to undergo questioning.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto was twice hospitalized last year, once for a mild
stroke and again for intestinal bleeding.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto was named as a suspect for alleged corruption during
his rule after Marzuki decided to reopen the case in December last
year.
</P>
<P>
U.S. business magazine Forbes last year estimated Soeharto's
family fortune at some 4 billion U.S. dollars. Time magazine, also
from U.S., has put the figure at about 15 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
