<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Join ASEAN Scheme to Monitor Foreign  Currency Traffic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia will join a cooperative
effort by ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian Nations) countries
to monitor foreign currency traffic to counter speculative
practices by international money brokers in the region.
</P>
<P>
"Indonesia should and will take part in such a cooperation, or
else we will get into trouble," Bank Indonesia Deputy Governor
Dono Iskandar Djojosubroto said.
</P>
<P>
Dono just attended an ASEAN Central Bank Forum in Bandar Seri
Begawan, capital of Brunei.
</P>
<P>
He said the policy of monitoring foreign exchange traffic with
countries within the region of ASEAN had been recommended by the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) and Indonesia supported the idea.
</P>
<P>
The IMF had also strongly suggested to widen the cooperation to
other countries in the Asia and Pacific region such as China,
Japan and South Korea, Dono was quoted by the Antara News Agency
Thursday as saying.
</P>
<P>
According to Dono, another outstanding topic discussed at a
meeting of ASEAN finance ministers in Bandar Seri Begawan was
Japan's proposal for the creation of an Asian Monetary Fund (AMF).
</P>
<P>
The proposal, forwarded by Japan for the first time in 1997,
was fully supported by ASEAN countries despite strong opposition
from the United States and the European Economic Community which
had argued that the AMF's activities would duplicate the IMF's.
</P>
</TEXT>
