<HEADLINE> Ethnic Albanian Leaders Oppose Serb Refugee Return to Kosovo: UNHCR </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, March 22 (Xinhua) -- Ethnic Albanian leaders in
Kosovo do not want to see the return of refugees of other ethnic
groups, United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR)
Sadako Ogata said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Ogata told a news conference that over the past year ethnic
Albanian leaders have not only been against the return of non-
Albanian refugees, but have also sought to drive all remaining non-
Albanian residents out of the Yugoslav province, in serious
violation of the UNHCR principle providing for the return of all
refugees.
</P>
<P>
She said the UNHCR mission in Kosovo will do its best to
persuade Serbs in Kosovo not to leave their homeland.
</P>
<P>
During her visits to refugee camps in Smederevo and Kragujevac
on the same day, Ogata said that although all the refugees at the
camps said they wanted to return home, "safety conditions for
their return do not exist."
</P>
<P>
She reiterated the U.N. position that all ethnic groups,
including Albanians and Serbs, should co-exist in Kosovo
peacefully.
</P>
<P>
Ogata arrived in Belgrade earlier Wednesday for a visit to
Yugoslavia, during which she will tour some towns in Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
