<HEADLINE> Ukraine Seeks Resumption of EBRD Loan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, March 22 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine on Wednesday urged the
European Bank for Reconstruction and Development (EBRD) to resume
loans to support the country's construction of new nuclear
stations.
</P>
<P>
After talks with visiting EBRD Vice President Charles Frank,
Ukrainian Prime Minister Viktor Yushchenko told a press conference
that the Ukrainian government has been "responsibly" meeting its
commitments under agreements on bilateral cooperation programs.
</P>
<P>
He promised that his government would shut down the Chernobyl
nuclear station in accordance with regulations in the memorandum
signed in 1996 with the Group of Seven industrialized countries
and the Commission of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
In order to ensure Ukraine's energy supply after the shutdown,
Yushchenko said he hoped the EBRD loans earmarked for the
construction of nuclear stations in Rovno and Khmelnitskiaya will
be in place at an early date.
</P>
<P>
As of March 15, the bank had endorsed for Ukraine 1.4 billion
euros (about 1.32 billion U.S. dollars) in credits for 33 programs,
but only 380 million euros (about 358 million dollars) had been
disbursed.
</P>
<P>
Frank said the former Soviet republic has not fully carried out
its commitments, stressing that his bank will resume the loans for
building new nuclear power stations only after it sees the
timetable for the close of Chernobyl.
</P>
<P>
The nuclear station in Chernobyl developed terrible leaks in
April 1986 and repeatedly went wrong afterwards. Under the 1996
memo, Ukraine is to close the plant during the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
