<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Globe 2000 Environment Conference Opens in Vancouver </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VANCOUVER, March 22 (Xinhua) -- The Globe 2000 Conference and
Trade Fair opened here Wednesday kicking off a three-day
international discussion on systematic development of business and
environment.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Minister of Environment David Anderson said in an
opening speech that development calls for a new architecture based
on prudence, and the old style of environment management that
responded only to immediate problems should be discarded.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to delegates from some 50 countries, he emphasized
that human activity places a great strain on the global eco-sphere.
</P>
<P>
"With the population doubling every 80 years, we are on a
course that will exceed global productivity in several generations,
unless we drastically change our patterns of consumption," he
warned.
</P>
<P>
The minister pointed out that over the past 20 years, though
economies of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and
Development have grown by 40 percent, human activity has, at the
same time, increased production of waste by an identical 40
percent.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously, we have not yet turned enough of our attention to
efficiency," the minister said, urging the world to join in
creating the new environment architecture to ensure a strong
economy and a better quality of life.
</P>
<P>
Some 10,000 people attended the sixth biennial conference in
the western coast city of Canada, which focuses on three major
topics: energy and climate change, corporate environmental
strategies and global environmental markets.
</P>
<P>
About 400 technology exhibits are displayed to promote business
solutions to global environmental challenges such as climate
change and sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
The Globe 2000 Conference and Trade Fair is sponsored by the
Canadian government's Climate Change Action Fund and organized by
the Globe Foundation, a non-profit organization dedicated to
developing environmental business. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
