<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 22 (Xinhua) -- Doctors wanted center of the
Houston Rockets Hakeem Olajuwon to stop playing for up to three
weeks because of his disease.
</P>
<P>
After examining the NBA star, Dr. James Muntz said Wednesday: "
He is still having problems so we asked him to take some time off.
" "We told him he would probably be out two to three weeks and
that's getting toward the end of the season."
</P>
<P>
The NBA regular season ends April 19.
</P>
<P>
37-year-old Olajuwon was diagnosed March 1 with a disease that
restricts the flow of air through his bronchial passages during
heavy exercise, causing spasms in his lungs.
</P>
<P>
The breathing problem has limited Olajuwon's playing time. He
is averaging 24 minutes a game for the season. His numbers this
season are 10 points and six rebounds.
</P>
<P>
Olajuwon's career averages were 23.6 points and 11.8 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
Olajuwon missed seven weeks earlier in the season to recover
from hernia surgery. 
