<HEADLINE> Indonesian Female Weightlifter Indriyani Injuries  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian national weightlifting
coach Imron Rosadi expressed disappointment with Sri Indriyani's
injury, which likely will prevent her from competing in the 2000
Olympics Games in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
While accompanying Indriyani to the National Sports Council (
KONI) sports science commission, Imron said he would not force the
lifter to continue training because it could destroy her career.
</P>
<P>
Indriyani, who competes in the 48-kilogram division, was
training for the Olympics. She injured her right knee while
attempting to lift 110 kilograms earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
"She unexpectedly injured herself. I have been training her and
other weightlifters to become champions. I don't have any
intention to hurt them," Imron was quoted by the Jakarta Post
Thursday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Imron said during her Olympic training in Lampung province,
Indriyani had approached world-record lifts.
</P>
<P>
"She could lift 90kg in the snatch, or six kilograms better
than the world record of 84 kgs. She also lifted 115kg in the
clean and 120kg in the standard jerk. In the clean and jerk,
Indriyani could lift 112.5kg. She was close to the world record of
113kg," he said.
</P>
<P>
Imron also said Indriyani managed a total lift of 200kg in
October and on February 18. The world record was 192.5kg.
</P>
<P>
Indriyani said she would undergo physiotherapy to recover from
her injury. She was optimistic she would be able to compete in the
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Imron said another weightlifter Winarni, who competes in the 53-
kg division, had recovered from typhoid and had begun training.
</P>
<P>
Winarni can lift 117.5kg in the clean and jerk and would likely
have equaled the world record of 121kg before getting typhoid. In
the snatch, Winarni's lift equals the world record of 97.5kg.
</P>
<P>
"After lifting in the snatch, she got typhoid that night. I'm
only human, I can't make any mathematical estimations about
Winarni's chances in the Olympics. We are faced with health
problems here. After all, this is bad luck. This is a tough
challenge for me," he said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's female weightlifters earned three tickets to the
Olympics after finishing eighth at the World Weightlifting
Championship in Athens last year, with one gold and four silver
medals. The Indonesian Weightlifting, Powerlifting and
Bodybuilding Association is training four female weightlifters for
the Games.
</P>
<P>
Lisa Rumbewas, who competes in the 48kg division, is training
in South Kalimantan and Supeni (53kg) trains in South Jakarta.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
