<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Purified Wastewater to Replace Tap Water to Spray Beijing Roads </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Starting from mid-June, a large
wastewater treatment plant in Beijing will daily channel 100,000
tons of purified wastewater to spray the downtown roads as one of
the water-saving measures.
</P>
<P>
The project, the largest one in the Chinese capital, is
expected to be initiated soon and completed in mid-June at the
Gaobeidian sewage treatment plant. And then every day 200,000 tons
of purified wastewater, instead of tap water, will be transferred
to the Beijing No.1 Thermal Power Plant and another 100,000 tons
be used to water trees and grass patches and clean the main roads
in the city, said related officials.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Water Resources and the Beijing municipal
government predict that the city's annual water demand will be
around five billion tons annually before 2005, with a shortfall of
800 million to 1.6 billion tons a year, while the figures for the
year 2010 will be 5.2-5.4 billion tons and 1.2-2 billion tons
respectively.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
