<HEADLINE> Over Ten Percent Families Own Computers in Tianjin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Computer owning Families are
nearly doubled from last year in Tianjin, a port city close to
Beijing in north China, according to a survey recently.
</P>
<P>
More than 13 out of every 100 families in Tianjin now have
computers, and sending E-mail from and surfing on the internet are
becoming a daily routine activity for more and more citizens.
</P>
<P>
A gentleman surnamed Du, bought a computer for his son, a
second-year college student, and later he found that it deeply
attracted all the family members. "It is a pet of all of us," he
said, "and it makes our family life more interesting."
</P>
<P>
Like Du, many parents are eager to buy computers to arm their
children with skills and new knowledge, though they themselves can
not use them.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the Chinese brand computers with prices
around 6,000 yuan (about 720 US dollars) are especially popular
among the citizens. 
</P>
