<HEADLINE> Jordan Wants out of Sponsorship Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 22 (Xinhua) -- The former basketball star
Michael Jordan says he no longer wants to be a corporate pitchman
and has told his sponsors to gradually adopt new campaigns,
according to reports from Chicago.
</P>
<P>
The ex-Chicago Bulls guard and now part owner of the Washington
Wizards, has endorsed an array of products: Nike shoes and apparel,
MCI telephone service, Hanes underwear and Ballpark Franks.
</P>
<P>
"Now I don't want my name just used," Jordan said. "I want to
understand the business itself, see the value in something other
than just endorsing."
</P>
<P>
Jordan said that he can't palm a basketball because of an
injured finger.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Jordan had surgery to clean up the old injury. He
hopes that will put the problem to rest.
</P>
<P>
Jordan added that "I can still shoot. But I can't grip the ball
completely. I have a tough time picking it up off the dribble like
I used to." 
</P>
