<HEADLINE> Government Urged to Pass Laws to Save Ancient Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Over the past 20 years, the State Council has designated 99
cities with long or specialized pasts as "Historical Cities" to
help protect remains of the old days, according to today's China
Daily.
</P>
<P>
However, in recent years, people lured by the high returns of
real estate development have destroyed some historical buildings
during construction.
</P>
<P>
For example, most ancient streets in Zhejiang Province's
Dinghai County were ruined last summer to allow the construction
of commercial blocks.
</P>
<P>
During a two-day meeting this week in Beijing, Vice Minister of
Construction Zhao Baojiang said that his ministry and the State
Bureau of Cultural Relics are working on a regulation to protect "
Historic Cities".
</P>
<P>
Wang Shiren, a construction expert, noted at the meeting that
the most effective preservation methods is to re-use old buildings
in a way that does not call for changing their original
appearances. 
</P>
</TEXT>
