<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0030 GMT, March 23 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair Wednesday set the
health reform a top priority, calling for a shake-up in return for
the additional 2 billion pounds (3.2 billion U.S. dollars) funding
announced in the Budget.
</P>
<P>
Blair told the parliament that the need for new cash for the
National Health Service was clear - but said it must be
accompanied by "fundamental reforms".
</P>
<P>
In an unusual move, Blair was making his first ever statement
to the Commons on a domestic spending issue, a role normally taken
by a secretary of state, to show how important he believes the
changes are. (Britain-Health-Reform)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LOS ANGELES -- Global Internet usage is well on its way to
reaching 1 billion users by 2005, with over 300 million people
already logged on, according to a new research report released
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
As many as 150 million people worldwide plan to use the
Internet this year, said the report from the Angus Reid Group, a
Vancouver-based global market and social research company.
</P>
<P>
There were an estimated 40 million Internet users worldwide in
1996. The most recent estimates suggest global Internet usage has
reached 275 million users, according to the study based on a
sample of more than 28,000 Internet users in 34 countries.
Currently Internet usage remains highly concentrated in a few
countries. (Internet-Users)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton intends to make a
controversial decision this summer on whether to deploy an anti-
missile system despite a new delay in testing, a White House
official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"There is every reason why he should make this decision, "said
Leon Fuerth, national security adviser to Vice President Al Gore
and a member of the "principals" group of top foreign policy
advisers to the president.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the U.S. Defense Department announced that the next
test of the National Missile Defense (NMD) system will take place
on June 26, two months later than originally planned. (US-Clinton-
Missile)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Palestinian National Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat
arrived in Cairo Wednesday for talks on the latest development of
the Palestinian-Israeli peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
During his short visit, Arafat will confer with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak on the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's visit came one day after the resumption of the
Palestinian-Israeli negotiations in the United States and days
before Mubarak's trip to the U.S. on Saturday. He is expected to
coordinate with the Egyptian leader on the peace march.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The U.N. Security Council Wednesday called on
all warring parties to end hostilities immediately in the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC), saying that the new
development would affect the on-going deployment of U.N. peace-
keepers in the central African country.
</P>
<P>
A statement read to the press here, the president of the
Security Council, Anwarul Chowdhury of Bangladesh, said, "Council
members expressed their dismay at the new offensive launched in
the province of Kasai, which resulted in the seizure of the town
of Idumbe." (UN-DRC) 
</P>
