<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Appoints Hingis as Goodwill Ambasador for Polio Eradication </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 23 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization (WHO)
has appointed Martina Hingis, the world number one women's tennis
player, as its Goodwill Ambassador for Polio Eradication.
</P>
<P>
In her new role, Hingis Wednesday launched a campaign to raise
awareness and funds to help eradicate polio, a highly infectious
disease which can cause total paralysis in a matter of hours.
</P>
<P>
"As WHO Ambassador, I will do everything I can to smash this
frightening disease off the planet," said Hingis on launching "
Match Point Against Polio". "I think all children should have the
chance to be active, to use their legs to run around the
playground, to swim, kick a ball, or play tennis."
</P>
<P>
"Match Point Against Polio" will promote polio eradication and
encourage large pulic support and participation throughout the
year, particularly at the Grand Slam tennis tournaments. These
include the French Open, Wimbledon and the US Open.
</P>
<P>
As part of her campaign, Hingis will travel to a polio-endemic
country where she will help immunize children against the disease.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
