<HEADLINE> Athletes to Have unannouced Doping Tests before Sydney </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 22 (Xinhua) -- The IOC will launch an unannouced
out-of-competition test on one of every two athletes before the
start of the Sydney Olympics, the head of the World Anti-Doping
Agency (WADA) said on Wednesday in Lausanne, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
Canadian lawyer Dick Pound, an International Olympic Committee
(IOC) vice-president and chairman of the WADA board, told the
media after a meeting on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Pound said the testing will start in April for some federations
and all of them will conduct the tests by the end of June. He
contemplated as many as 2,500 tests under the program.
</P>
<P>
The IOC will use eight million U.S. dollars for the testing but
EPO (erythropoietin) will not be in the detection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
