<HEADLINE> SLA Militiaman Killed, 2 Injured in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 23 (Xinhua) -- One militiaman of pro-Israeli South
Lebanon Army (SLA) was killed and two others wounded Thursday
morning in attacks launched by Hezbollah guerrillas in Baet Leef in
south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel shortly bombed several villages in the western sector of
the Israeli occupied security zone as retaliation, damaging four
houses and a mosque. But there were no immediate reports of
casualties.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the Syrian-backed resistance movement
Amal issued a statement, saying they launched two missile and
mortar attacks on Israeli positions and hit the targets Thursday
noon.
</P>
<P>
Israel carved out a so-called "security zone" in 1985 in south
Lebanon with the claimed aim to protect its north from cross-border
guerrilla attacks.
</P>
<P>
The SLA, funded and controlled by Israel, helps the Jewish state
patrol the "security zone."
</P>
<P>
On March 5, Israeli cabinet decided to withdraw Israeli troops
from south Lebanon by July this year, with or without an agreement
with Lebanon and its powerbroker Syria. But Hezbollah repeatedly
announced they will not forgive the SLA militiamen that were
regarded as traitors.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian and Syrian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, is
waging a guerrilla war trying to oust Israeli troops and the SLA
from south Lebanon.  
</P>
</TEXT>
