<HEADLINE> Egypt, Tunisia Sign Agreements on Cooperation in Different Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Egypt and Tunisia signed here on
Thursday a number of agreements and executive programs aimed at
promoting bilateral cooperation in different fields.
</P>
<P>
The agreements were inked at the end of the two-day eighth
session of the Egyptian-Tunisian Joint Higher Committee under the
co-chairmanship of the two countries' prime ministers, Egypt's
Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Among the pacts are an agreement aimed at promoting trade, an
executive program in the areas of youth and sports, three memoranda
of understanding on standardization, education, technology and
specifications accreditation.
</P>
<P>
The pacts also include an agreement on cooperation in social
security, two protocols on technical cooperation, an executive
program on vocational training and another on educational
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the two sides signed a pact on joint cinema
production.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the closing session, Egyptian Prime Minister Atef
Obeid underlined his country's keenness on further boosting trade
and economic relations with Tunisia in a bid to increase the trade
volume to 300 million U.S. dollars in the coming years from 81
million dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
Obeid said the coming few years will witness more meetings,
projects and support for the implementation of the signed
agreements.
</P>
<P>
His Tunisian counterpart Mohamed al-Ghannouchi expressed
appreciation for Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak's interest and
efforts in boosting cooperation with Tunisia.
</P>
<P>
Al-Ghannouchi underlined the importance of creating favorable
atmosphere for business, trade exchange and joint projects between
his country and Egypt in an effort to help advance the process of
setting up a common Arab market.
</P>
<P>
Al-Ghannouchi arrived in Cairo later Tuesday at the head of his
country's delegation to the joint committee meetings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
