<HEADLINE> Sudan, Kuwaiti Fund Sign MOU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Sudan and the Kuwaiti Fund for
Economic Development (KFED) signed a memorandum of understanding
here on Thursday on the settlement of Sudan's debts to the KFED
amounting to 33 million Kuwaiti dinars (about 107.63 million U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Sudan had used the KFED's money to finance various water, road
and power projects, according to the Sudanese News Agency (SNA).
</P>
<P>
The two sides held talks over the last two days on the
settlement of the debts, SNA quoted an official of the Sudanese
ministry of finance and economy as saying.
</P>
<P>
The document paved the way for normalization of relations
between Sudan and the KFED, the official said, pointing out that
the latter financed the initiation of 11 projects.
</P>
<P>
The KFED delegation expressed the desire of the Kuwaiti leaders
to normalize ties with Sudan, he added.
</P>
<P>
Regarding other Arab financiers, the official said Sudan had
normalized its ties with the Abu-Dhabi Fund and the Saudi Fund, and
would do so with the Arab Monetary Fund soon.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese-Kuwaiti ties have been strained since the second
Gulf War in 1990 when Sudan backed Iraq in its invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
</TEXT>
