<HEADLINE> U.N. Panel On Peacekeeping Operations to Meet In May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 23 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. panel on
peacekeeping operations concluded their inaugural session
Wednesday and agreed to meet next at the end of may in London, U.N.
spokesman Fred Eckhard said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Eckhard said U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, at the opening
session, urged them to think broadly and imaginatively about
practical ways that the U.N.system as a whole might better respond
to threats to international peace and security.
</P>
<P>
The panelists discussed structure of the study and the report
itself, and agreed on the ways they would maintain a dialogue
among themselves throughout the process, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The panelists hoped to meet again in the second half of July
at U.N. Headquarters to discuss and review the actual text of the
report, which the Secretary-General asked to be submitted that
month, the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief announced the establishment of the panel on
March 7, which is headed by former Algerian Foreign Minister
Lakhadar Brahimi. The panel is expected to finish its work in July.
</P>
</TEXT>
