<HEADLINE> EU's Nomination of IMF Head Accepted: Portuguese PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Guterres announced the acceptance during the summit of EU heads
of state and government who are discussing the issue of employment
Thursday and Friday in Lisbon.
</P>
<P>
French President Jacques Chirac and German Federal Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder congratulated Guterres on his way in which he
handled the delicate negotiations which led to the EU re-
nomination of Horst Koelher for the top job of the IMF.
</P>
<P>
The post was left open after the departure of French incumbent
Michel Camdessus.
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation bloc originally nominated German deputy finance
minister Caio Koch-Weser for the post but the United States
opposed to the nomination on the ground that the German was not
well qualified for the job.
</P>
<P>
The EU then nominated Horst Koelher as a substitute in the race
for the IMF managing director. Koelher currently runs the
European Bank for Reconstruction and Development and the bank
channels international aid funds to the former Soviet republics.
</P>
<P>
Koelher is respected in Europe for his role in the preparation
for the creation of the single currency -- euro.
</P>
<P>
The post of IMF managing director has been customarily held by
a European while an American has been holding the top job of the
World Bank. But Stanley Fischer of the United States has joined
Japanese Eisuke Sakakibara in the pursuit for the IMF managing
director. 
