<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany, U.S. Achieve Breakthrough in Holocaust Compensation Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BERLIN, March 23 (Xinhua)-- Germany and the United States
Thursday made a key breakthrough in Berlin in their 11th round
negotiation over how to compensate the survivors of Nazi slave
labor system.
</P>
<P>
After more than one year of talks in Washington, Bonn, and
Berlin, the two governments, central and east European countries,
the Jewish groups, and the German business finally achieved an
agreement on the allocation of the 10-billion-mark German
foundation.
</P>
<P>
Under their plan, each former slave laborer in Nazi
concentration camps will get 15,000 mark as compensation, and
laborers forced to work in German firms in Nazi regime are due to
get 5,000 marks each.
</P>
<P>
Totally, over one million Nazi slave and forced labor victims
will get 8.10 billion marks as direct compensation. The sum will
reach 8.15 billion after being increased by interest earnings of
50 million marks.
</P>
<P>
And one billion marks are prepared for the losses of public
property caused by Nazi. Some 700 million marks will be allocated
for a "Future Fund" for historical and educational memorials.
</P>
<P>
The German cabinet Wednesday passed a draft "Foundation Law"
that committed the half-to-half contributions of German government
and business to the 10-billion-mark foundation. The bill is due be
passed in German parliament, the Bundestag, in this July.
</P>
<P>
A group of Switzer banks are expected to add further 100
million marks to German foundation initiative.
</P>
<P>
Two governmental representatives, Otto Graf Lambsdorff of
Germany and Stuart Eizenstat of the U.S., called Thursday's
agreement "a huge step forward."
</P>
<P>
"All participants defended their positions vigorously, but all
recognized the larger imperative of reaching agreement now, so
that the funds could promptly go to survivors," Eizenstat, U.S.
deputy Finance Secretary, said at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
"I am pleased to report that all participants have agreed on
our joint proposal, this should not have been done without all
parties' flexibility and compromise," he added.
</P>
<P>
Eizenstat said the compromise was "a fair agreement that takes
account of the interests of all parties."
</P>
<P>
The German business is not fully satisfied with the agreement
while what it wanted, a "judicial conclusion" from Washington, is
remained for further talks as last important issue.
</P>
<P>
Under a German-U.S. agreement in last December, U.S. courts
will protect German companies from victims' further compensation
claims as repaying for their participation in the foundation.
</P>
<P>
According to Manfred Gentz, the representative of German
business in the talks, 676 German firms have agreed to join the
foundation initiative and they have paid 2.3 billion marks.
</P>
<P>
But Washington will still wait until the Bundestag passes the
Foundation Law before giving German business any promise, said
Eizenstat.
</P>
<P>
"The final law will be the linchpin of the legal settlement, I
can not overemphasize this point," he said, adding, "the German
legal basis for the foundation will be examined carefully by our
courts." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
