<HEADLINE> U.S. Replaces Patriots in Gulf, South Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 23 (Xinhua) -- The United States has replaced
hundreds of Patriot missiles deployed in the Gulf and South Korea
after discovering a problem with the air defense system, the
Pentagon said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Pentagon spokesman Navy Rear Adm. Craig Quigley told reporters
that the problem could be in the missile's ability to receive a
radio frequency downlink that helps guide them to their speeding
targets, although nothing had been confirmed.
</P>
<P>
The missiles were withdrawn from approximately 11 batteries in
the Gulf and South Korea. Each battery has about 64 missiles.
</P>
<P>
Raytheon Co., which build the weapon, said it was working with
the U.S. Army to find the cause of potential flaws in the system.
</P>
<P>
"Raytheon is working with the Army to identify and resolve the
problem," said Raytheon spokesman Dave Shea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
