<DOCNO> XIE20000323.0366 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Special Representative For Iraq Phased Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 23 (Xinhua) -- The post of the United
Nations Special Representative For Iraq was being phased out
entirely, U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Indian diplomat Prakash Shah was named by U.N. Secretary-
General Kofi Annan in 1998 as U.N. Special Representative for Iraq
to coordinate relations between Iraq and the United Nations,
especially in connection with U.N. arms inspections in the country.
</P>
<P>
Last August his status was changed from that of a full-time U.
N. employee based in Baghdad to employment on an as needed basis,
returning to Iraq only when required.
</P>
<P>
"In the light of the Security Council's new plan for
inspection and monitoring in Iraq, the Secretary-General considers
that a Special Representative is not required at this time,"
Eckhard said
</P>
<P>
"He has informed Mr. Shah and thanked him for his contribution
over the past two years as the Secretary-General's Special
Representative," the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Security Council last December adopted a
resolution on Iraq which created the U.N. Monitoring, Verification
and Inspection Commission to replace the United Nations Special
Commission in charge of dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass
destruction.  
</P>
</TEXT>
