<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Appoints Koehler as New Managing Director </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 23 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) on Thursday selected Germany's Horst Koehler as its new
managing director to succeed France's Michel Camdessus, who
resigned in mid-February this year.
</P>
<P>
"The Executive Board of the International Monetary Fund today
agreed unanimously to select Horst Koehler as Managing Director
and Chairman of the Executive Board of the International Monetary
Fund," the IMF said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Koehler, a former German finance ministry official who now
heads the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development, was
the Europe Union's second candidate to head the IMF. The first
nominee, Caio Koch-Weser, withdrew from the race this month after
the United States said it would not support him.
</P>
<P>
"I am deeply honored that the membership of the IMF has placed
its trust in me as its new managing director," Koehler said in a
statement released in London on Thursday. "I look forward to
working closely with all member countries and with the fund staff
to meet the challenges ahead."
</P>
<P>
Koehler, 57, will take office at a difficult time for the IMF,
which is under fire in the U.S. Congress and elsewhere for its
response to the world financial crisis of 1997-99.
</P>
<P>
A controversial report to U.S. Congress wants the IMF to curb
its lending activities sharply, eliminating concessionary loans to
poor countries and lending only to countries which had "pre-
qualified" for financial help.
</P>
<P>
Testifying before the House Banking Committee on Thursday, U.S.
Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers said that some of the more
radical ideas could put U.S. security at risk by preventing the
lender from helping a wide range of countries.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that taken literally they would straitjacket these
institutions to the point where they would no longer be able to
advance America's core values," Summers said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000323.0368 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unemployed Demonstrate Outside EU Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LISBON, March 23 (Xinhua) -- At least around 50,000 people took
to the Lisbon streets on Thursday to demand quality employment and
fight against poverty outside the European Union summit.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators, organized by local trade unions, filed
through streets from downtown Lisbon to the old municipal
exhibition center that houses the two-day summit of EU heads of
state and government that is focusing on the issue of employment.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators came from various parts of the country and
from various professions. Some police even estimated the total
number of demonstrators as many as 100,000, unprecedented in the
Portuguese capital.
</P>
<P>
Unemployment has long been haunting the EU citizens and the EU
leaders as well. EU-wide, some 15 million men and women remain
jobless, corresponding to 8.8 percent of the active population of
the 15-nation bloc.
</P>
<P>
Three years ago, however, the jobless population was 18 million
and the figure has been reduced by a million each year in the
ensuing two years.
</P>
<P>
Yet still the average unemployment rate for the European Union
was at 9.6 percent in January this year, with Spain at the highest
end of the gamut with 15.1 percent and Luxembourg at the other end
with 2.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
France, Finland and Germany are also suffering from alarming
unemployment rates at 10.3 percent, 10.0 percent and 8.8 percent
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The European Union tried to reduce the unemployment sore in
December 1997 but ended up with only a declaration of intent to
fight the scourge.
</P>
<P>
The Lisbon summit of EU heads of state and government is
expected to come out with some detailed time limits for certain
employment-orientated objectives to be achieved.
</P>
<P>
Portugal, that is holding the six-month rotating presidency of
the union, proposed to set an annual growth rate of 3 percent as
one of tangible measures to boost employment while the EU leaders
are expected to decide on a shift onto e-commerce to help enlarge
employment of available work force.
</P>
<P>
Local demonstrators demanded the Portuguese authorities to work
out some detailed measures and timetable to help improve job
creation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
