<HEADLINE> More Demonstrations in Costa Rica Against Reform Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of workers and students
marched Thursday from the central park in the Costa Rican capital
to the Presidential House, to protest against the approval of a
law of reform for the Costa Rican Energy Institute (ICE).
</P>
<P>
The Costa Rican radio and television reported that the
demonstrators occupied several kilometers of streets that lead to
the Presidential House in the capital, which partially paralyzed
vehicular traffic.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators marched peacefully shouting slogans like "The
ICE yes, no to the combo" (combo is what the ICE reform law is
called).
</P>
<P>
The country authorities asked the citizens to maintain order
and prudence, not to cause disturbances and repeated that the ICE
will not e sold, while the labor unions were distributing
pamphlets in which they insisted on 20 reasons for which the ICE
must not be reformed or privatized.
</P>
<P>
If the government does not desists, the demonstrations will
continue to the end, they said. Workers of hospitals and
insurance, companies, as well as educators also took part in the
march.
</P>
<P>
The most important ports in the Pacific and the Atlantic
suspended their operations, and the Costa Rican Oil Refinery also
was paralyzed in Puerto Limon, which could create a possible fuel
supply crisis Thursday and Friday.
</P>
<P>
Many stores in the capital closed their doors as a preventive
measure to avoid possible damage.
</P>
<P>
The situation continues tense, so President Miguel Angel
Rodriguez canceled Wednesday the trip he had programmed to the
United States, because of any unforeseen incident.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
