<HEADLINE> Colombian Police Capture Rebel Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, March 23 (Xinhua) -- Colombian police intelligence
services agents have captured Revolutionary Armed Forces of
Colombia (FARC) 14th front leader Gildardo Gonzalez, who has been
charged with the killing of three U.S. missionaries in January
1998, authorities said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Gonzalez was detained in Saravena municipality in the
department of Arauca.
</P>
<P>
The authorities said that Gildardo Gonzales identified himself
with a citizenship identification card to the name of Nelson
Vargas Rueda, issued in Tibu, Norte de Santander province.
</P>
<P>
The insurgent chief was sought together with German Briceno
Suarez, also known as "Grannobles," for kidnapping, torture and
assassination of Terence Freitas, a 24-year-old environmentalist,
and two women of American Indian background, Ingrid Washinawatok,
41, and Laheenae Gay, 39.
</P>
<P>
The bodies of the three U.S. missionaries were abandoned with
signs of torture in the Colombia-Venezuela border zone.
</P>
<P>
The FARC claimed the responsibility of the kidnapping and
assassination some days after finding the bodies, saying that it
was an action of rebels who did not consult with FARC commanders.
</P>
</TEXT>
