<HEADLINE> Europe's Leading Stocks Continue To Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, MARCH 23 (Xinhua) - London stock market dipped for the
third straight session Thursday pressured by declines in oil and
drug issues.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark FTSE 100 in London closed down 15 points,or 0.2
percent, at 6594.6, recovering from a midday decline of more than
70 points, helped by a late-day return to the plus column by
Vodafone AirTouch.
</P>
<P>
Heavyweight oil producer BP Amoco dropped 3.1 percent and rival
Shell Transport &AMP; Trading fell 1.5 percent after crude prices
eased on news that the U.S. had passed a bill confirming American
President Clinton's power to cut off aid and arms sales to OPEC
members.
</P>
<P>
Drug stocks felt faint. SmithKline Beecham fell more than 2.5
percent, while sector rival Glaxo Wellcome, which announced
earlier this year it plans to merge with SmithKline, slipped 3.2
percent.
</P>
<P>
Germany's Dax index ended near its day's low as falls in
technology and car stocks outweigh gains by HypoVereinsbank and
reinsurer Munich Re on speculation of a possible tie-up.
</P>
<P>
The Xetra Dax 30 index lost 1.33 percent, or 103.84 points, to
end at 7694.78.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, the CAC 40 ended down 10.98 points at 6268.31, a dip
of 0.2 percent, with sharp gains in France Telecom helping to
limit losses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
