<DOCNO> XIE20000323.0382 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Says Political Commitment of Parties Concerned Is Precondition for Success of DDR Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 23 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Security Council on Thursday stressed that the political
commitment of the parties involved in a peace process is a
precondition for the success of the disarmament, demobilization
and reintegration(DDR) of the ex-combatants.
</P>
<P>
The move came after the Security Council held one-day long
open debate on the role of the United Nations peacekeeping
operations in the disarmament, demobilization and reintegration of
the ex-combatants.
</P>
<P>
In a presidential statement, the Council underlined DDR of ex-
combatants are mutually supportive and that the success of the
process is dependent on the success of each of its steps.
</P>
<P>
The Council reaffirmed that DDR must take place in a secure and
safe environment, which will give ex-combatants the confidence to
lay down their arms and underlined the importance of international
assistance for long term economic and social development to
facilitate successful reintegration.
</P>
<P>
The Council noted that DDR must be addressed comprehensively so
as to facilitate a smooth transition from peacekeeping to peace-
building.
</P>
<P>
The Council underlined in particular the importance of DDR of
child soldiers as well as taking into account the problems faced
by war-affected children in mission areas.
</P>
<P>
The Council welcomed the initiative of the U.N. Secretary-
General to include within all peacekeeping operations personnel
with appropriate training in international humanitarian, human
rights and refugee law, including child and gender related
provisions.
</P>
<P>
The Council stressed that training of peacekeepers in DDR of ex-
combatants continues to be an important asset in the
implementation of these activities in mission areas.
</P>
<P>
The Council encouraged the U.N. Secretary-General to continue
to address this issue on a regular basis and to draw to its
attention any new developments in this area.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
